<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>  <div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" class="tei_body"><section class="paratext" id="index.xml-body.1_div.1"><header><h1><span class="head">Notebook 1 of Dorothy Wordsworth’s <em>Rydal Journals</em><br/> <span style="font-size: 75%">(DCMS 104.1, 11 December 1824–9 December 1825)</span></span></h1></header></section><br/><hr/><br/><section class="section" id="index.xml-body.1_div.2"><header><h1><span style="font-size: 75%">[List of expenditures inside front cover]</span></h1></header><figure class="figure"><img src="PLACEHOLDER.png" alt="Figure 1: Inside front cover and first page of DCMS 104.1" class="block" style=" width:400px;"/></figure><div class="wrapper"><p>Mr H’s hams<br/> 3 – 12 – 4 ½ <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note1" id="Note1_return"><sup class="super">
            (1)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>This running log of DW’s purchases follows the conventional pounds-shillings-pence bookkeeping format. See left side of scan in figure 1. </span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p>Miss Greenhow for D <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note2" id="Note2_return"><sup class="super">
            (2)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>This unspecified purchase for Dora (D) possibly came from Ann Greenhow of Kendal, who specialized in wrappers, twine, and other packaging products (see WG, 8 June 1822).</span></div></div> <span class="indent3">11 – 6</span><br/> Blank silk for D<sup>r</sup> &amp;<br/> Ws handkerchief <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note3" id="Note3_return"><sup class="super">
            (3)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Presumably gifts for DW’s brothers Christopher (D r) and WW (W).</span></div></div> – – <span class="indent2">11</span> – 3<br/> Teaspoons <span class="indent7">2 – 6</span><br/> Turnpikes &amp;c 1 – –<br/> Miss [Cherberleys?] 7 – 6</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p>Excursion to Ulverston Etc.<br/> <span class="indent2">July 5–8</span> <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note4" id="Note4_return"><sup class="super">
            (4)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>A curatorial note in pencil and a hand other than DW’s that references this notebook’s detailed account of her July 1825 trip to Ulverston. </span></div></div></p></div></section><section class="section" id="index.xml-body.1_div.3"><header><h1><span style="font-size: 75%">[December 1824]</span></h1></header><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday December 1<sup>st</sup>, 1824</span><br/> Ground thinly covered with snow. Snow showers – rain – hail. Walk before dinner, <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note5" id="Note5_return"><sup class="super">
            (5)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The major daily meal, usually eaten between 2:00 and 4:00 p.m. during this period. GJ suggests that, at least two decades earlier, the Wordsworths typically dined closer to 2:00 p.m. (60).</span></div></div> with M &amp; W. After to Mr Carr’s – – still hail-showers – frosty moonlight returning with <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Carr">Mr &amp; Mrs Carr</a>. Fine clouds Day &amp; Night.</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 2<sup>nd</sup></span> Bright morning. Hills &amp; valley white – With Mary at <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Elliotts">Mr Elliotts</a> – very cold there[.] Walk first with W – then alone under Crags <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note6" id="Note6_return"><sup class="super">
            (6)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Nab Scar, roughly a mile northwest of Rydal Mount. </span></div></div> in Sun &amp; after Dinner with Wm – –</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 3<sup>rd</sup></span><br/> Still hard frost – not cloudless – Threating snow – Bottle wine <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note7" id="Note7_return"><sup class="super">
            (7)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Raisin wine (as clarified in ensuing entry). Cf. GJ, 19 (1 September 1800) and Letters, 3:409.</span></div></div> – With Wm. to Ambleside, after dinner</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 4<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Clear frost – Bottled Raisin Wine – Dined at 2 – Wm at Grasmere meeting <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note8" id="Note8_return"><sup class="super">
            (8)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>WW vocally opposed the proposed enclosure of waste and common lands in Grasmere and Loughrigg at several local meetings that winter (Letters, 4:304, 8:187–90).</span></div></div> – Walk with Willy to Ambleside – in wood by Scandal. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note9" id="Note9_return"><sup class="super">
            (9)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Scandale Fell, roughly a mile northeast of Rydal. </span></div></div> Mr &amp; Mrs Carr to tea <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note10" id="Note10_return"><sup class="super">
            (10)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The traditional British afternoon repast, usually taken at this time between 5:00 and 6:00 p.m. DW’s GJ entry for 13 February 1802 characterizes 7:30 p.m. as unusually late for tea (68).</span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 5<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Very bright morning – Alpine Lights on hills – Ambleside Church – <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Hartley">Hartley Coleridge</a> to dinner – <a class="link_ref" href="editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Marshall">Mr Marshall</a> called. All day bright – glorious Moon – burr <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note11" id="Note11_return"><sup class="super">
            (11)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>A circle of light or halo.</span></div></div> round it &amp; yesterday –</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 6<sup>th</sup> Decr</span><br/> Thaw, heavy rain – clears before 4. Walk on Terrace <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note12" id="Note12_return"><sup class="super">
            (12)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The 250-yard-long terrace WW had developed upon moving to Rydal Mount for gazing upon Rydal Water and to have a place to pace as he wrote poetry. On 21 January 1825, he expressed his regrets to Lord Lonsdale for having been away when the lord had recently called, as he “should have liked much to show [him] the view from the garden and Terrace of Rydal Mount, which are universally admired” (Letters, 4:305–06).</span></div></div> – amber Clouds – To Ambleside with [ ] &amp; Dora – Full Moon, tip toe, on dark Cloud – lost again. Rose by Candle light – W. too late for Coach <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note13" id="Note13_return"><sup class="super">
            (13)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The coach that was to take him and Dora to Keswick (see following entry). A coeval letter of MW reports how on this visit WW stayed with Robert Southey and Dora with “the solitary Mother of her friend Mary Calvert, who was married last Autumn” (WT MS WLL / Wordsworth, Mary / 1 / 64).</span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 7<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Dull morning – a little rain – went to Mrs Elliotts – letters from Wales <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note14" id="Note14_return"><sup class="super">
            (14)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Likely updates from Tom Hutchinson, MW’s brother who had just moved from Radnorshire, Wales, to Brinsop Court, Herefordshire, near the Welsh border. </span></div></div> &amp;c – [Jos.?] <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note15" id="Note15_return"><sup class="super">
            (15)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Perhaps the Joseph referenced in Mary Ann Lloyd’s later account of how, in 1825, the Wordsworths’ staff included “Joseph the farming-boy who had the charge of the Pony, and when at Rydal the care of the Poultry” (WLMS A / Jewsbury, Maria Jane / 52). </span></div></div> goes by Coach. Wm &amp; D follow on horseback – Showers – yellow brightness to the South[.] Walk on Terrace. Stormy ride to <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Keswick">Keswick</a>…</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 8<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Windy &amp; showery – [nary?] out –. After dinner walked to Quarry <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note16" id="Note16_return"><sup class="super">
            (16)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Possibly the quarry on the eastern shore of Rydal Water near Nab Wood. Another nearby quarry is memorialized in the title of WW’s 1800 poem 
        “Lines Written with a Slate-Pencil upon a Stone, the Largest of a Heap Lying near a Deserted Quarry, upon One of the Islands at Rydale.”
      </span></div></div> with Mary. – No rain. – <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Wilson">Fanny Wilson</a>. Letter from Dr W. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note17" id="Note17_return"><sup class="super">
            (17)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>DW and WW’s younger brother Dr. Christopher Wordsworth. </span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 9<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Fine morning. Sunshine, but soon a hail shower – All day showery &amp; cold –. Wrote to Miss Horrocks <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note18" id="Note18_return"><sup class="super">
            (18)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Sarah Horrocks, whose sister Jane was married to Tom Monkhouse, MW’s seriously ill cousin. The Monkhouses and Sarah had gone to Torquay on the Devon coast hoping the sea air would improve Tom’s health. DW wrote on 13 December that “Miss Horrocks” had been “very good in sending [them] whatever tidings she receives from Torquay” (Letters, 4:291).</span></div></div> – a little rain going to Ambleside with M. Call at <span class="ref">Mrs North’s</span>[,] Mrs Carlton’s, <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note19" id="Note19_return"><sup class="super">
            (19)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Mary Chambers Carleton, whose husband, John, had died in Ambleside in 1820 at age 73 (WG, 18 November 1820). The family moved to the Lakes from Ireland in 1814 after John was charged with embezzling public funds in his capacity as a Dublin alderman (see Stewart, “Carleton Family of Eustace Street”; “Alderman John Carleton, a Bankrupt,” Saunders’s News-Letter [Dublin], 16 February 1815).</span></div></div> <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Knott">Miss Knott’s</a>, Thomas Troughton. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note20" id="Note20_return"><sup class="super">
            (20)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Stationer and bookseller in Ambleside from ca. 1820 until his 1860 death (Kendal Mercury, 23 June 1860).</span></div></div> Bright frost at 11.</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 10<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Very keen bright frost – – continues – only hazy in the afternoon. Bottled wine – <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Dowling">Miss M[ary] Dowling</a> to dinner. Rainy night.</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 11<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Misty rain – walked with M &amp; Willy to <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Fox">Fox Ghyll</a> – wrote <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Luff">Mrs Luff</a>. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note21" id="Note21_return"><sup class="super">
            (21)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Visiting Margaret De Quincey, who had just delivered her fifth child in the absence of her husband, Thomas. After this visit, DW updated Mrs. Luff on the De Quinceys’ timeline for leaving Fox Ghyll (see Letters, 4:282–83, 317–18).</span></div></div> Heavy rain at Keswick. Wm. &amp; Dora cannot come on horseback – arrive in Coach. J W. arrives. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note22" id="Note22_return"><sup class="super">
            (22)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>John Wordsworth, returning from Oxford for the holidays (LMW, 121). Partly over fears of a typhus outbreak in Oxford, he would not return to school until after Easter (Letters, 4:292, 298).</span></div></div></p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 12<sup>th</sup></span> – Very warm &amp; mild. All at Church but Dora &amp; Willy. – They at Ambleside. Called at <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Campbell">Col. Campbell’s</a>, very wet returning.</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 12<sup>th</sup></span> <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note23" id="Note23_return"><sup class="super">
            (23)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>After incorrectly dating consecutive entries the 12th, DW’s numbering would be off for several weeks. She later corrected the dates for 19–22 December but neglected to change those from the previous week. </span></div></div> <br/> Very dark morning. – Breakfast at 8. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note24" id="Note24_return"><sup class="super">
            (24)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Probably specifies the hour because the leisured classes of this period generally did not eat breakfast until 9:00 or 10:00 a.m. </span></div></div> – Rain all day. – – wrote letters, walked on Terrace, while Wm &amp; J go to Ambleside – dark night</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 13<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Very rainy – all day. Began Dante. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note25" id="Note25_return"><sup class="super">
            (25)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>DW’s abiding interest in Dante is evidenced in her copious, undated notes on his life and works in DCMS 119. </span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 14<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Rain! Rain! I went to Miss Dowlings &amp;c. – Chaises going. Mr Cowper <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note26" id="Note26_return"><sup class="super">
            (26)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Likely the Ambleside tradesman DW mentioned in a 27 March 1821 letter (Letters, 4:52).</span></div></div> very ill – Starlight at 11 – &amp; frost</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 15<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Beautiful rose-coloured sky. Mild morning – no frost[.] Fox Ghyll with W at ½ past 1. Mrs Carlton – Rain comes on Terrace – wet evening.</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 16<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Rainy morning – not heavy. <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Wilkinson">Peggy Wilkinson</a>. Dante. Walk on Terrace after dinner 2 hours – a little Rain. Coach Lamps – <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Robinson">Mrs Robinsons</a> to supper <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note27" id="Note27_return"><sup class="super">
            (27)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Generally, a lighter meal eaten at 9:00 or 10:00 p.m. </span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday <br/> 17<sup>th</sup></span> <br/> Very Dark morning. Misly <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note28" id="Note28_return"><sup class="super">
            (28)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Drizzling.</span></div></div> rain. Meeting at G[rasmere]. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note29" id="Note29_return"><sup class="super">
            (29)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>See note for 4 December.</span></div></div> Mr Harrison <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note30" id="Note30_return"><sup class="super">
            (30)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Anthony Harrison, a friend of WW’s since their time at Hawkshead grammar school and now a Penrith solicitor, part-time poet, and agent for Lord Lonsdale. </span></div></div> &amp;c. – – Wet all day. –</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday <span style="text-decoration: line-through">18</span> 19<sup>th</sup></span> Wm. to Lowther[.] I in Chaise to Ambleside <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note31" id="Note31_return"><sup class="super">
            (31)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>After Harrison spent the night of 17 December at Rydal Mount, he and WW made the 23-mile trip to Penrith in his chaise, dropping DW off in Ambleside en route. WW was visiting his ailing associate, Rev. James Clarke Satterthwaite, one of the region’s most influential Tories (Letters, 4:304; LMW, 120–21).</span></div></div> – Mr Carr’s – Rain all day</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday <span style="text-decoration: line-through">19</span> 20<sup>th</sup></span> Bright sunrise – rain comes on –. With M to <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Ivy">Ivy Cot</a> and <a class="link_ref" href="Cottage">Ivy Cot</a>, &amp; Scandal Hill. Cold, sleety, hail &amp; rain all day. Lightning as [ ] [later rain?]</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday <span style="text-decoration: line-through">20</span> 21<sup>st</sup></span><br/> Fresh snow on [waking?]. Fine morning – Blue sky &amp; large clouds – heavy rain comes on. Party at <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Betty">Betty’s</a> and <a class="link_ref" href="Dawson">Betty’s</a>. Hail showers &amp;c &amp;c</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday <span style="text-decoration: line-through">21<sup>st</sup></span> 22<sup>nd</sup></span><br/> Dark morning. After breakfast on Terrace – [All?] the rest of the day – Rain, sleet, &amp;c &amp;c – [ ] wind [–] frosty night</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 22<sup>nd</sup></span><br/> Sudden keen frost – very bright. Wm. expected – [up to?] Ambleside with John[,] Dora <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Barber">Mr Barber’s</a></p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 24</span><br/> No frost – sunshine – – at Mr E[lliott]’s with <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Myers">Julia</a>. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note32" id="Note32_return"><sup class="super">
            (32)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Dora reported on 27 December, “Julia Myers . . . is spending her Holy days with us” (WT MS WLL / Wordsworth, Dora / 1 / 6).</span></div></div> Wm arrives <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note33" id="Note33_return"><sup class="super">
            (33)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Returning from the visit to Lowther for which he had departed on 19 December. </span></div></div> –</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Christmas Day</span> <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note34" id="Note34_return"><sup class="super">
            (34)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>DW’s fifty-third birthday.</span></div></div> Storm – wind rain flood – Chapel opened <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note35" id="Note35_return"><sup class="super">
            (35)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Of the torrential rain that spoiled the opening of the new Rydal Chapel commissioned by Lady Ann le Fleming of Rydal Hall, Dora wrote, “I never was out in such a storm, nor does my Father ever remember experiencing so violent a one. . . . It was truly awful” (WT MS WLL / Wordsworth, Dora / 1 / 6). WW grumbled that “the cost of the Structure has much exceeded what was needful” but conceded that “when time has softened down the exterior a little it will prove a great ornament to the Village grateful” (Letters, 4:301). MW considered it a great monument to the Village,” “notwithstanding all the bl…</span></div></div> – Water [pills?] – Cards</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 26<sup>th</sup></span> <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note36" id="Note36_return"><sup class="super">
            (36)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Dates are again slightly off for the final five entries of December 1824, as the 26th was a Sunday, the 27th a Monday, and so forth. </span></div></div> <br/> Very dark – very wet morning. Party at Mr Robinson’s. Just fair for our walk thither[.] Mrs Carr in Chaise</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 27<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Fine day – rather frosty. Mr Douglass, <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note37" id="Note37_return"><sup class="super">
            (37)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Likely the same person DW alludes to in an April 1825 letter that mentions “Mr Douglas’s swindling tricks” (Letters, 4:340).</span></div></div> Mrs Elliotts[.] Moonlight walk to Ambleside. Very fine –</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 28<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Frosty – fine sun-rise – clear sky – To Fox Ghyll &amp; Ambleside. Rain comes on in the evening, after Walk on Terrace</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 29<sup>th</sup></span> – not frosty but fine day – rather windy – Rain at night</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 30<sup>th</sup></span> – William’s tooth drawn. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note38" id="Note38_return"><sup class="super">
            (38)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The first of several dental extractions recorded in the RJ, adding to several in the GJ (e.g., pp. 12, 103, 133). During an 1820 visit to London, DW had paid 50 guineas to have her six remaining teeth pulled and replaced with dentures. WW would follow suit in 1836 (Barker, 534, 680).</span></div></div> Rainy morning. Fair to Mr Carr’s to dinner – very windy &amp; very warm</p></div></section><section class="section" id="index.xml-body.1_div.4"><header><h1><span style="font-size: 75%">[January 1825]</span></h1></header><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">New years day </span>– Fine morning – to Church. To <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Robinson">Mr Robinson’s</a>. <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Jackson">Mr J[ackson]</a> <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note39" id="Note39_return"><sup class="super">
            (39)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>On 10 December 1824, MW apologetically informed their old neighbor (and Dora’s future husband) Edward Quillinan, “In the course of the Holidays we shall have Mr Wm Jackson for our guest[;] therefore the Mount cannot receive you” (WT MS WLL / Wordsworth, Mary / 1 / 64).</span></div></div> &amp; Miss Hodson <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note40" id="Note40_return"><sup class="super">
            (40)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Possibly a relative of Frances Barlow, whose mother was a Hodson.</span></div></div> call – very wet afternoon</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 2<sup>nd</sup></span><br/> Strong cold wind – I went to Grasmere Church[.] Rain in showers, in returning. Mary Party – first night <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note41" id="Note41_return"><sup class="super">
            (41)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>MW seems to have hosted a New Year’s, or “First Night,” party. </span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 3<sup>rd</sup></span><br/> Very Rainy all day – clear night. Mr R’s Twins born <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note42" id="Note42_return"><sup class="super">
            (42)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Although the Robinsons lived in Ambleside, the Cumberland Pacquet for 11 January 1825 listed their twins’ place of birth as Rydal. The delivery may have occurred, then, at Rydal Mount, which might explain Mr. Carr’s presence.</span></div></div> – – <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Carr">Mr Carr</a> to dinner &amp;c.</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 4th</span><br/> Mary at Grasmere, I wrote letters for Wm. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note43" id="Note43_return"><sup class="super">
            (43)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Among these was a lengthy letter to their brother Christopher (Letters, 4:296).</span></div></div> – to <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Dowling">Miss Dowlings</a> before dinner – dry cold wind – frosty night. Very clear</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 5<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Beautiful frosty day [–] Sunny. <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Harden">Mrs Hardens</a> with Wm &amp; over <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Loughrigg">Loughrigg</a> <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note44" id="Note44_return"><sup class="super">
            (44)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>In his Guide to the Lakes, WW recommended this favorite route overlooking Grasmere Lake and Rydal Water, observing, “There are delightful rambles over every part of Loughrigg Fell and among the enclosures on its sides; particularly about Loughrigg Tarn, and on its eastern side about Fox How and the properties adjoining to the northwards” (link to our Guide ed., para. 15 of 1835 text).</span></div></div> – Reading [Madam?] [ ].</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 6<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Dull morning – frosty. <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Calgarth">Calgarth</a> &amp; <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Troutbeck">Troutbeck</a>. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note45" id="Note45_return"><sup class="super">
            (45)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Presumably visiting the Watsons and perhaps the Barlows.</span></div></div> Rain comes on – Detained in Troutbeck – Darkness, dull moonlight – misty rain</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 7<sup>th</sup> Jany. 1825</span><br/> Rain &amp; Mist. Clears in afternoon. After Dinner I walked to Grasmere. Met W &amp; Mr Robinson. Bright frosty night.</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 8<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Bright sun, inclining to frost. Walk with W &amp; M to <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Fox">Fox Ghyll</a> and <a class="link_ref" href="Ghyll">Fox Ghyll</a> thro wood – on Terrace –.</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 9<sup>th</sup></span> – Lovely day at Grasmere – clear &amp; bright. Silvery Fogs on Rydal hills &amp;c. – Wm Green <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note46" id="Note46_return"><sup class="super">
            (46)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Unidentified. While there were several Rev. William Green’s in Britain, none were in the northwest. Accordingly, this might have been Rev. Daniel Green, a son of Grasmere just then entering the ministry after graduating from St. Catherine’s Hall, Cambridge (see 27 July 1825 entry and Letters, 4:218n6).</span></div></div> preached. After [to?] Rydal church[,] at Mrs Robinsons &amp; walk on Terrace. Clear there[.] Fogs below remind me of Rigi &amp; Lenzberg. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note47" id="Note47_return"><sup class="super">
            (47)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>DW, WW, and MW visited Mount Rigi and Lenzburg in central Switzerland during their 1820 continental tour. DW’s 4 August 1820 entry in her Journal of a Tour on the Continent reads, “Lenzburg. . . . At six o'clock we caught a glimpse of the castle walls glittering in sunshine, a hopeful sign, and we set forward through the fog.” Her entry for 19 August, when they reached the “Top of Rigi,” makes no mention of fog.</span></div></div></p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday </span>– Grey &amp; rather foggy – mending stockings &amp;c – Called with Mary at <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Scambler">Mrs Scambler’s</a> – (no rain) &amp; Miss Dowling’s</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 11<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Wm went to Cockermouth <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note48" id="Note48_return"><sup class="super">
            (48)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Town 28 miles northwest of Rydal where WW and DW were born. This four-day trip was possibly connected to WW’s duties as Distributor of Stamps. </span></div></div> – Lovely sunshine comes out after grey morning. I to <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Wilson">Fanny Wilson’s</a>, Mrs Green’s, Mary Kirby’s <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note49" id="Note49_return"><sup class="super">
            (49)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Anne Green was the 40-year-old widow of William Green, the renowned Ambleside artist who had died in 1823. Mary Kirby may have been a former servant of the Wordsworths, judging from DW’s use of her first name. In a letter dated 27 December 1824, Dora appears to insinuate she would soon give birth out of wedlock, writing, “I am very sorry to say that poor Mary Kirby expects every day to be confined [–] this is one cause why Mr G has staid so long away [–] it is very lucky for Mary that he is away” (WT MS WLL / Wordsworth, Dora / 1 / 6).</span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 12<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Fine bright day – a little frosty … I walked – to Stone Man <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note50" id="Note50_return"><sup class="super">
            (50)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Likely Stone Arthur on the southwestern edge of Great Rigg (see GJ, 41, 201n).</span></div></div> &amp;c on Loughrigg – Calling – Mrs Scambler to tea</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 13<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Grey &amp; mild – a <span style="text-decoration:underline">little</span> soft Rain. With Mary to Ambleside to Mrs Carr’s, Mrs Green’s, Mr Courtnay <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note51" id="Note51_return"><sup class="super">
            (51)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Philip Courtenay (1782–1842), barrister and political operative who often functioned as WW’s business agent (Letters, 4:121–22, 309).</span></div></div> – – – N.B. Since Monday, 1 Book of Dante per day</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 14<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Grey morning – soft rain[.] Walk with M. to Fox Ghyll: – very warm</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 15<sup>th</sup></span><br/> All day rain. Wm. comes from Cockermouth</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 16<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Very rainy. Church at Rydal – not cold.</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 17</span><br/> Sunny morning, yet slight showers. Opened Mr E[lliott]’s windows. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note52" id="Note52_return"><sup class="super">
            (52)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>MW and DW were helping maintain Ivy Cottage between tenants. See MW’s report on 10 December: “I must now be off to close the windows – for the sun very, very soon leaves that gem of a Cottage &amp; the frosty air will do it no good” (WT MS WLL / Wordsworth, Mary / 1 / 64).</span></div></div> Called at P Kirby’s, <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note53" id="Note53_return"><sup class="super">
            (53)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Unidentified but presumably a relative of Mary Kirby (see note for 11 January). </span></div></div> <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Betty">Betty Dawsons</a> and <a class="link_ref" href="Dawson">Betty Dawsons</a>. Old Woman fallen down stairs. After tea, beautifully bright. Miss J[ane] Dowling calls – D. at Mr North’s. Wm &amp; I walked to Ambleside – gentle Rain then, – &amp; a wet night. Letter from <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Sara">Sara</a> better news <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note54" id="Note54_return"><sup class="super">
            (54)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>SH was in Torquay helping care for Tom Monkhouse, who had momentarily taken a turn for the better (see note for 9 December). </span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 18<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Very rainy – very dark – clears – windy &amp; rather cold – – Walk with <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Myers">Julia</a> &amp; Mr R to John [Hester’s?] – <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Dixon">Betty Dixon</a> – handsome present <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note55" id="Note55_return"><sup class="super">
            (55)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Presumably a gift for Betty’s newborn, Diana (born 9 January). </span></div></div></p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 19<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Very wet – not cold[.] Mr Carrs Dinner – to Ambleside alone in evening. Dark &amp; Dirty … no rain –</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 20<sup>th</sup></span> Wet morning – [ ] with Mr R to Mr Douglass’s[.] <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note56" id="Note56_return"><sup class="super">
            (56)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>See note for 27 December.</span></div></div> Windy – [snowy?] cold – At Mr Elliotts</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 21<sup>st</sup></span><br/> hail showers – rain showers. After dinner 2 hours on Terrace &amp; at Mr E[lliott]’s. – Reading [Burke?] [ ] at [ ] [ ].</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 22<sup>nd</sup></span><br/> Bright frosty morning. Walked with Mr R, by Fox Ghyll, to field above Mr Jackson’s <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note57" id="Note57_return"><sup class="super">
            (57)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>During his tenure as Rector of Grasmere, Rev. Thomas Jackson, father of William Jackson, maintained a farm at Langdale, roughly three miles west of Rydal.</span></div></div> – Enchanting sunny view</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 23<sup>rd</sup></span><br/> Very bright day at Rydal Church – With Miss E[liza] D[owling] after dinner to Ambleside.</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 24<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Gloomy frost. D at <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Barbers">Mr Barbers</a>. With Wm &amp; Willy to Grasmere. Skates carried[.] Ice would not bear Snow at Night</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 25<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Deep snow – sunshine[,] frost. With John to Ambleside after dinner – called at Mr Carr’s.</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 26<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Snow again – William to <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Low">Low Wood</a> and <a class="link_ref" href="Wood">Low Wood</a> – I to Ambleside. Thaw &amp; rain –.</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 27<sup>th</sup></span> – – rain</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 28<sup>th</sup></span> – a fine day</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 29<sup>th</sup></span> Rainy – I went to <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Kendal">Kendal</a> <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note58" id="Note58_return"><sup class="super">
            (58)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>DW spent 29 January–15 February in Kendal with the Cooksons. In a 13 February letter, she wrote, “It was a fortnight yesterday since I came to Kendal, intending to stay but a week, however my kind Friends have been so unwilling to part with me that, having no particular object to call me home, I could not refuse” (Letters, 4:315).</span></div></div></p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 30<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Rainy. I not well. [ ] fine sky &amp; clear frost – snow – &amp; flood<br/> --------------------<br/> Remained at Kendal till</p></section><section class="section" id="index.xml-body.1_div.5"><header><h1><span style="font-size: 75%">[February 1825]</span></h1></header><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 15<sup>th</sup> February</span>– Mizzling rain in cart with Edwin <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note59" id="Note59_return"><sup class="super">
            (59)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The Cooksons’ youngest son. In her 13 February letter, she reported, “On Thursday, if weather be tolerable, Edwin is to go with me to Rydal. . . . He is a proud child at the thought of his journey. He says to me two or three times every day—‘I am going with you to Rydal!’ and talks of the Waterfalls and all that he is to see” (Letters, 4:316).</span></div></div></p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 16<sup>th</sup></span> very fine &amp; bright[,] warm</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 17<sup>th</sup></span> – very wet. <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Luff">Mrs Luff</a> came</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 18<sup>th</sup></span> – Lovely bright day</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 19<sup>th</sup></span> – [Mild?] gloom. – I walked to Grasmere, round [brakes?] – wrote to <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Campbell">Mrs Campbell</a> &amp; <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Elliott">Mrs Elliott</a></p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 20<sup>th</sup></span> – Very bright &amp; fine</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 21<sup>st</sup></span> – Lovely day – sunny. – Morris’s funeral <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note60" id="Note60_return"><sup class="super">
            (60)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Likely Wilson Morris, a local laborer who had done odd jobs for the Wordsworths as recently as November 1824 (Letters, 4:135, 168; WT MS WLL / Wordsworth, Mary / 1 / 63).</span></div></div> – wrote to Sara, <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Tillbrooke">Tillbroke</a>, Miss Horrocks <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note61" id="Note61_return"><sup class="super">
            (61)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>See note for 9 December 1824 entry.</span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 22<sup>nd</sup></span><br/> Fine grey warm day – Walked with M. to Mrs [Tresway?], Mrs Harding’s, <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note62" id="Note62_return"><sup class="super">
            (62)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Both unidentified. The latter is possibly a misspelling of Mrs. Harden. </span></div></div> &amp;c &amp;c. Mary’s tooth drawn</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 23<sup>rd</sup></span><br/> Grey and cold. To <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Carr">Mr Carrs</a>[,] Market, Mrs Luff’s alone</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 24<sup>th</sup></span> – grey &amp; cold but no wind – no rain since Thursday week – with Mary to Mrs Luffs &amp; <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Fox">Fox Ghyll</a> and <a class="link_ref" href="Ghyll">Fox Ghyll</a>. Miss <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Dowling">E[liza] D[owling]</a> to dinner. <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Knott">Miss Knott</a>, Mrs Huddleston <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note63" id="Note63_return"><sup class="super">
            (63)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Widowed aunt of the Wordsworths’ neighbor and landlord Lady Ann le Fleming, who had signaled she might not renew their lease at Rydal Mount so Mrs. Huddleston could live there. </span></div></div> – Met Wm &amp; walk on Terrace ... not well soon to bed. Began Dante again</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 25<sup>th</sup></span> – Cold &amp; grey – D &amp; W to <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Calgarth">Calgarth</a> and <a class="link_ref" href="Hall">Calgarth</a> – I to Mr Carr’s evening.</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 26<sup>th</sup></span> – Snow – with Willy to Mrs Luff’s to tea</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 27<sup>th</sup></span> – Sunshine. Snow falling in Flakes – – Star light &amp; frost</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 28<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Very cold – snow again. Received the Tidings of our dear Friend T Monkhouse’s Death (on Saturday 26) at Clifton <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note64" id="Note64_return"><sup class="super">
            (64)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>An extreme instance of DW’s almost clinical approach throughout much of RJ, belying how devastated she and the rest of the family were upon learning Tom Monkhouse had died at Clifton (near Bristol) at 41. Cf. the significantly more detailed, grief-ridden account DW sent Catherine Clarkson 12 days later (Letters, 4:324–26).</span></div></div></p></div></section><section class="section" id="index.xml-body.1_div.6"><header><h1><span style="font-size: 75%">[March 1825]</span></h1></header><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday <span style="text-decoration: line-through">29<sup>th</sup></span> 1<sup>st</sup> March</span><br/> Very cold. Snow covering hills &amp; fields – walked to <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Fox">Fox Ghyll</a> and <a class="link_ref" href="Ghyll">Fox Ghyll</a>[.] <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Luff">Mrs L[uff]</a> there</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 2<sup>nd</sup></span><br/> Thick snow – &amp; snow late afternoon – walk on Terrace after dinner – again snow.</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 3<sup>rd</sup></span><br/> Snow still falling – – walk on Terrace after dinner – – &amp; now (12 o’clock) a thick covering – trees all white –.</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 4<sup>th</sup></span> More snow – and frosty clear night [–] walk on Terrace</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 5<sup>th</sup></span> Lovely sunshine – dazzling hills – a Skin of Ice on Rydal Lake – long walk on Terrace</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 6<sup>th</sup></span> – Cold Thaw &amp; Rain</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 7<sup>th</sup></span> – Dull Thaw – Bright Evening. <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Southey">Mr Southey</a> arrives. No snow at <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Keswick">Keswick</a> <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note65" id="Note65_return"><sup class="super">
            (65)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>This weather report was courtesy of Southey, who was visiting from Keswick. MW noted on 25 February 1825 that he had delayed this planned visit by several weeks (Letters, 4:324).</span></div></div> – sate on Shore of Lake on Saturday – <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note66" id="Note66_return"><sup class="super">
            (66)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>A rare instance in which DW works in a neglected detail from a previous day, as she generally scribbled any such omissions in the margins or between the lines of the entry for the day in question. This perhaps explains why DW or someone else has added a small question mark in the MS between “Shore” and “of.” “Sate” is an archaic form of “sat.” </span></div></div></p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 8<sup>th</sup></span> – Slow dull Thaw</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 9<sup>th</sup></span> – Wet &amp; dull[.] Still warm. John does not get off.</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 10<sup>th</sup></span> – John goes <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note67" id="Note67_return"><sup class="super">
            (67)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>DW reported on 13 February that “John Wordsworth will be going to Whitehaven before the end of this month, to stay till Easter” with William Jackson (Letters, 4:316).</span></div></div> – mild &amp; dull – small, soft rain. The <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Carr">Carrs</a> to dinner &amp; <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Robinson">Mr R.</a></p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 11<sup>th</sup></span> – Mild pleasant day –</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 12<sup>th</sup></span> – very fine – warm but coldish in the evening.</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 13<sup>th</sup></span> – cold &amp; rainy[.] Mrs Luff in afternoon. I drank tea with her</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 14<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Sunny morning – very cold – breakfasted with Mr J[ackson] – to Ambleside, about <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Hartley">Hartley’s</a> [will?] – grey cold afternoon. Walk in garden, on Terrace, Birkhagg field. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note68" id="Note68_return"><sup class="super">
            (68)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Birk Hagg, a wood just north of Rydal.</span></div></div> <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Elliott">Mrs E[lliott]’s</a> with D. Thermom. at freezing point. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note69" id="Note69_return"><sup class="super">
            (69)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Thermometer readings appear regularly in later RJ notebooks, but this is the only such mention n Notebook 1.</span></div></div></p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 15<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Bleak cold morning – snow [begins?].</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 16<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Still gloomy &amp; cold, but pleasant walking[.] <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Harden">Mrs Harden’s</a> with M. Mrs D <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note70" id="Note70_return"><sup class="super">
            (70)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Unidentified. She possibly meant “Miss D,” for Miss Dowling. </span></div></div> &amp;c.</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 17</span> – Bright &amp; cold, very pleasant. <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Barber">Mr Barbers</a>[.] New Road &amp;c (all.) Willy’s accident. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note71" id="Note71_return"><sup class="super">
            (71)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Apparently not a major injury, as this is the only reference to it in RJ or surviving letters. The entire family appears to have gone to Barber’s via the road that had just opened between Rydal and Grasmere. Comparing this new route (which remains the main thoroughfare today) and the old one, the Penny Magazine explained in June 1837, “Between Rydal and Grasmere the high road formerly ran winding among, and over a succession of knolls; and being half hidden in its serpentine course, afforded a series of exquisite views, without deforming this lovely valley. But the steepness of the hills was i…</span></div></div></p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 18<sup>th</sup></span> – Snow – – Fox Ghyll[,] Terrace &amp;c.</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 19 </span>– Bright, cold, busy in gardens.</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 20<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Very Bright – Bishops Ladies <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note72" id="Note72_return"><sup class="super">
            (72)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Presumably the Watsons, the wife and daughters of the late Bishop of Llandaff.</span></div></div> at Chapel – walk after with W &amp; M on new Road [–] beautiful Evening</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 21</span><br/> Again fine – – not quite so sunny – &amp; coldish air but very pleasant at Grasmere – [with?] Mrs Luff &amp; [walk?]</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday </span>delightful in morning but Grey. At Grasmere with Mrs Luff &amp; Aggy <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note73" id="Note73_return"><sup class="super">
            (73)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Although an Aggy Fisher and Aggy Black had worked for the Wordsworths, this was likely Agnes (“Aggy”) Ashburner, the hard-luck daughter of their former Grasmere neighbors Thomas and Peggy (see GJ, 41). MW reported in 1810, “Poor Aggy Ashburner is in the same situation as her sisters without having any hope of being made an honest woman of. . . . As to Aggy’s self she has I find little feeling about it—she is, which I never knew before, only a half-wit—poor Soul” (WT MS WLMS / G / 1 / 2 / 7). In the intervening years, the Wordsworths had occasionally hired Aggy Ashburner to do odd jobs (Letters…</span></div></div> &amp; walk with W &amp; M.</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday </span>– very bright – air not warm – clear – delightful. Mrs Blakeney’s Sale. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note74" id="Note74_return"><sup class="super">
            (74)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Since the recently widowed Margaret Edwards Blakeney (d. 1828) had just sold Fox Ghyll to Mrs. Luff, this multiday moving sale (see ensuing entry) disposed of furnishings from the home. DW writes of the appeal of such sales in the Green narrative, and De Quincey characterized them as highlights of the Westmorland social calendar, attracting rich and poor with the promise of free liquor (at the seller’s expense), occasional bargains, and chances to meet up with friends one rarely saw either because of “real distance” or the “virtual distance” that “results from a separation by difficult tracts …</span></div></div> I called at <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Knott">Miss Knott’s</a> after Tea – good news. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note75" id="Note75_return"><sup class="super">
            (75)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Presumably about an upturn in this chronically ill acquaintance’s health. </span></div></div> Lovely Crescent Moon &amp; one Star at the Tip – exquisitely bright – Mr R. with me</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday <span style="text-decoration: line-through">23rd</span> 24</span><br/> Colder air – very bright – Second Sale Mrs B[lakeney’]s. After Tea with Mary to Ambleside</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 25<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Dullish in the morning – Then very Bright – The Askews <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note76" id="Note76_return"><sup class="super">
            (76)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Family of Rev. Henry Askew of Greystoke, near Penrith (see Letters, 3:395).</span></div></div> call –. After dinner with Wm &amp; M to Fox Ghyll. Met Mrs Luff to tea. [Hired?] her servant</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 26<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Still very fine. Sauntered much – with Mr R after dinner to <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Wilson">Fanny Wilson’s</a></p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 27<sup>th</sup></span> – still fine – Grasmere Church with D. Hartley C to dinner – with Wm. to Grasmere Hill – home by moonlight – air warmer – very fine – beautiful sunset</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 28<sup>th</sup></span> – Very fine</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 29<sup>th</sup></span> – The same. Always cold in the mornings, &amp; all-day Sun</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 30<sup>th</sup></span> – Fine, but a little cloudy – <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Sarah">Mrs C[oleridge] &amp; Sara</a> and <a class="link_ref" href="Coleridge">Mrs C[oleridge] &amp; Sara</a> arrive <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note77" id="Note77_return"><sup class="super">
            (77)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>DW reported on 4 May that “Mrs Coleridge and Sara went home 10 days ago after 3 weeks and 3 days happy stay – They both enjoyed themselves much” (Letters, 4:346). See also Sara Coleridge’s account of their stay in WT MS WLMS A / Coleridge, Sara / 9.</span></div></div> – very fine evening – Walk on W. side of R[ydal] over Bridge &amp; on new Road –</p></div></section><section class="section" id="index.xml-body.1_div.7"><header><h1><span style="font-size: 75%">[April 1825]</span></h1></header><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday April 1<sup>st</sup></span> Very fine – walk with W – on White Moss <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note78" id="Note78_return"><sup class="super">
            (78)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>An unenclosed common and tarn between Rydal Water and Lake Grasmere renowned for its scenic views and memorialized in “Resolution and Independence” as the site of WW and DW’s famous encounter with the long-suffering leech-gatherer. In the GJ for 2 June 1802, DW wrote, “This White Moss a place made for all kinds of beautiful works of art &amp; nature, woods &amp; valleys, fairy valleys &amp; fairy Tairns, miniature mountains, alps above alps” (104).</span></div></div> – new Road home</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 2<sup>nd</sup></span> Still fine – –</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 3<sup>rd</sup></span><br/> Never [seemed?] sunshine. I with <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Sara">Sara</a> &amp; [W?] after dinner – White Moss</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 4 (Easter)</span> Wm, M, &amp; D. to Church</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 5 </span>Lovely day –. Walk alone to Grasmere after Tea. Most calm &amp; beautiful – Sir R<sup>d</sup> Fleming’s <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note79" id="Note79_return"><sup class="super">
            (79)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>A cousin of the Flemings of Rydal Hall who became Grasmere’s rector in 1822. Soon after his arrival, DW noted, “Sir Richard le Fleming has had the living for some weeks, and is settled in the Parsonage House. He has given us 3 excellent sermons and two very bad ones – we fear the good are exhausted” (Letters, 4:149).</span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 6 </span>– Again very fine &amp; hot – To Ambleside. <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Tillbrooke">Mr Tillbroke’s</a> linen. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note80" id="Note80_return"><sup class="super">
            (80)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Presumably, retrieving Tillbrooke’s washed linens in preparation for his impending stay at the recently vacated Ivy Cottage and Ivy Cottage.</span></div></div></p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 7<sup>th</sup> –</span>The same &amp;c.</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 8<sup>th</sup> April</span>D[itt]<sup>o</sup></p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 9<sup>th</sup></span> – as fine as ever</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 10<sup>th</sup></span> – A little gloom at night – a few Drops of Rain. Starlight</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 11<sup>th</sup></span> – Very bright – to Grasmere Church with W – Cold in the Evening.</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 12 </span>Rain – cold – –</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday</span> – a little Rain – snow on hills</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday</span> Cold &amp; Dry – sunny. – To <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Harden">Mrs Harden’s</a> with <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Sara">Mrs C[oleridge]</a> and <a class="link_ref" href="Coleridge">Mrs C[oleridge]</a> &amp;c. Mrs P’s Sale <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note81" id="Note81_return"><sup class="super">
            (81)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Unidentified. On sales, see note for 23 March entry.</span></div></div> [–] Jane Harden [to?] [ ] <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note82" id="Note82_return"><sup class="super">
            (82)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The Hardens’ 18-year-old daughter, Jane Sophia.</span></div></div></p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday</span><br/> A little Rain. <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Dowling">Miss E[liza] D[owling]</a> to tea. – –</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday </span>a little rain</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday</span> dry &amp; cold –</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 18<sup>th</sup> April</span><br/> Sunny &amp; cold air</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 19<sup>th</sup></span> – Dry.</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 20<sup>th</sup></span> – The same &amp; sunny – sharp air.</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 21<sup>st</sup></span><br/> at <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Low">Low Wood</a> and <a class="link_ref" href="Wood">Low Wood</a> with Wm[.] Mild Rain – warm air</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday</span><br/> Very fine clear air [–] sunshine – – –</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday</span><br/> Cold – – a little sun</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday </span>cold &amp; dry – Mrs Coleridge left us.<br/> N B. all last week, no downright Rain, but much refreshing down[ful?], till the cold sets in.</p></section><section class="section" id="index.xml-body.1_div.8"><header><h1><span style="font-size: 75%">[May 1825]</span></h1></header><div class="wrapper"><p>Showery weather from the 21<sup>st</sup> April till now <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note83" id="Note83_return"><sup class="super">
            (83)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>That is, 1 May, when she resumes her journal. </span></div></div> – Never all-day rain, &amp; often delightful – half a sunny day or more – – –</p></div><p>-----------</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">May 1<sup>st</sup></span> – fine morning. <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Barlow">Mrs &amp; Miss Barlow</a> <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note84" id="Note84_return"><sup class="super">
            (84)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Thrown together through much of the summer of 1825 with Fanny Barlow, Dora never fully took to the 17-year-old heiress. On 6 August she confided to Maria Jane Jewsbury, “I do like Miss Barlow but the ‘attachment’ is at its height – it will never get beyond liking I fear” (Letters, 4:378).</span></div></div> to dinner – Rain in afternoon – – a little colder</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 2<sup>nd</sup></span> – Busy with <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Robinson">Mrs Robinson</a> &amp;c &amp;c – – still raining</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 3<sup>rd</sup></span> – – Cold – with rain – &amp; intervals of Dry [–] wrote to Sara [Hutchinson], <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Cookson">Miss Cookson</a>, <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note85" id="Note85_return"><sup class="super">
            (85)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Elizabeth, the Kendal Cooksons’ 25-year-old daughter. Despite her chronic illnesses in early adulthood, she would live to age 92 (Carlisle Patriot, 27 March 1891; Letters, 4:315–17).</span></div></div> <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Elliott">Mrs Elliott</a> – letter from Miss Horrocks. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note86" id="Note86_return"><sup class="super">
            (86)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>See note for 9 December 1824 entry.</span></div></div></p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 4<sup>th</sup></span> – – Rain again, not heavy</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 5<sup>th</sup></span> – Rain – air close – – Thunder on air</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 6<sup>th</sup></span> – very close <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note87" id="Note87_return"><sup class="super">
            (87)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Humid and stuffy. </span></div></div> – &amp; hot. Thunder showers – head-ache [–] wrote letters. – Letters to Coleridge &amp;c. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note88" id="Note88_return"><sup class="super">
            (88)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The letter to STC is apparently lost, but see DW’s 4 May letter to Catherine Clarkson conveying STC’s request for a favor (Letters, 4:344–45).</span></div></div> Violent thunder elsewhere [–] man killed on Lane</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 7<sup>th</sup></span> – Very hot &amp; close[.] Heavy showers in afternoon – fair morn – clears and we walk to Grasmere.</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 8<sup>th</sup></span> – Showery, cool again –. Walk with Wm. to Grasmere, &amp; Spring-cottage, <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note89" id="Note89_return"><sup class="super">
            (89)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The house next to Fox Ghyll where Mrs. Luff resided while her new home was under renovation. </span></div></div> and after tea with <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Luff">Mrs Luff</a> to <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Fox">Fox Ghy[ll]</a> and <a class="link_ref" href="Ghyll">Fox Ghy[ll]</a></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 9<sup>th</sup></span> – Very bright &amp; clear – light air – Mr Pearson spending day – Ruins pulled down <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note90" id="Note90_return"><sup class="super">
            (90)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>William Pearson (1780–1856) was a local antiquarian and admirer of WW’s poetry who had retired in his native Crosthwaite after a career as a Manchester banker (see Letters, 4:143). Since his correspondence with WW often touched on the region’s antiquities, he presumably had informed them about the pulling down of some nearby ruins.</span></div></div> – Mrs Luff at Whitehaven</p></div><p>-----------</p><p>All the week neglected Diary. Only one wet day. Books arranged &amp;c &amp;c</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 15<sup>th</sup> May</span>– very fine &amp; bright – I went to Grasmere Church –</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 16<sup>th</sup></span> – grey &amp; cool. Wm at Mrs Barlow’s</p><p>All the Rest of the week as fine as possible – bright Sun, but a little cold nights &amp; mornings. </p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday (i.e. yesterday) May 20<sup>th</sup></span> spent with Wm. in going to Dun-mail Rays[,] he intending to go to <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Keswick">Keswick</a> – courage failed &amp; came under Helm, &amp;c – &amp; visit Larch Grove Waterfall <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note91" id="Note91_return"><sup class="super">
            (91)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>See Dora’s 21 May account (misdated 28 May in Letters) of how WW and DW “started yesterday but when they got to the top of the Raise [Dora’s] Father found himself ‘too weak’ to proceed. They spent the day in the Fields of Grasmere and reached home to a latish Tea” (4:351). After turning back at Dunmail Raise—the pass five miles northwest of Rydal that divides the valleys of Grasmere and Thirlmere—they would have passed under Helm Crag after a mile and a half and crossed Thomas King’s larch groves at The Hollens after another two miles.</span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday <span style="text-decoration: line-through">22<sup>nd</sup></span> 21</span><br/> Busy at <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Ivy">Ivy Cot</a> and <a class="link_ref" href="Cottage">Ivy Cot</a>, &amp; with Letters – no reading this week – all bustle in two houses. – Carpets made &amp;c &amp;c. Beautiful Day. <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Dowling">Miss Eliza Dowling</a> &amp; 6 young Ladies <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note92" id="Note92_return"><sup class="super">
            (92)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Cf. Dora’s corroborating report of being interrupted by “the arrival of a party of young ladies from Miss Dowling’s to tea – Julia [Myers] among them” (Letters, 4:352).</span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 22<sup>nd</sup> – Whitsunday</span> <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note93" id="Note93_return"><sup class="super">
            (93)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The English equivalent of Pentecost, celebrated seven weeks after Easter. </span></div></div> – at Grasmere Church – no communicants but Robert Newton &amp; myself <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note94" id="Note94_return"><sup class="super">
            (94)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>A communicant is one who receives Holy Communion, or the sacrament of the Lord’s Supper, and Robert Newton was an old Grasmere innkeeper who appears several times in GJ (see 171n, 172n). DW’s report of the dismal turnout on this holy day lends credence to WW’s complaint earlier that year about how “in this Country . . . there is a sad want of zeal among Members” of the Established Church (Letters, 4:301).</span></div></div> – very fine day. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note95" id="Note95_return"><sup class="super">
            (95)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>This same day DW wrote in a letter to SH, “Spring-time is as delightful as the beginning, and Rydal more beautiful than ever. – Lilacs, Laburnums, and Roses all in full bloom” (Letters, 4:353).</span></div></div> Came home over Crags <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note96" id="Note96_return"><sup class="super">
            (96)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Nab Scar.</span></div></div> – <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Harden">Mrs Harden</a> &amp;c at Rydal – seen at a distance</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 23<sup>rd</sup></span><br/> Very fine cleaning study. Mrs Cookson &amp; 3 children, Mr C[ookson], Miss C[ookson] &amp; <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Jewsberry">Miss Jewsberry</a> arrive – – various walks &amp; [visiting?] after a stop to Dust &amp; Labour among the Books – Much pleased with young Ladies – struck with Miss J. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note97" id="Note97_return"><sup class="super">
            (97)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The Wordsworths were uniformly enchanted with the 25-year-old Jewsbury, a virtual stranger a month earlier who by summer’s end had become a family favorite and Dora’s “dearest friend” (LSH, 305; LDW, 22–28).</span></div></div> Rain in the night –</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 24<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Rather cloudy morning. Wm with the party at Stock Gill &amp;c. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note98" id="Note98_return"><sup class="super">
            (98)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Stock Ghyll Force, the waterfall just east of Ambleside. </span></div></div> M. &amp; I putting up Books – washing carpet – threatening sky but no rain in afternoon – –</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 25<sup>th</sup></span> – Rainy morning, clears &amp; we go to <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Langdale">Langdale</a> &amp;c – Fair day. Mr Wilson met all Langdale <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note99" id="Note99_return"><sup class="super">
            (99)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The party followed a route WW had recommended in the 1822 edition of his Guide to the Lakes: “From Ambleside is a charming excursion, by Skelwith-fold and Colwith-force up Little Langdale, Blea Tarn, Dungeon-ghyll waterfall (if there be time) and down Great Langdale” (Description of the Scenery of the Lakes, 140). The inclusion of John Wilson (1785–1854, DNB), the eminent poet and critic and part-year resident of the Lakes, is somewhat surprising, as his once-close bond with the Wordsworths had been severely strained by his occasional rough handling of WW, Coleridge, and Southey—and myriad oth…</span></div></div> – Thompson &amp; Family <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note100" id="Note100_return"><sup class="super">
            (100)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Possibly the proprietor of the gunpowder mill recently opened in the Langdale valley near Elterwater (see note for 11 June entry). </span></div></div> – no doors open at Dungeon Ghyll – dined in the Barn –. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note101" id="Note101_return"><sup class="super">
            (101)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Likely at Millbeck Farm, a still-running eighteenth-century farm near Dungeon Ghyll Force. In her 1855 Complete Guide to the Lakes, Harriet Martineau advises, From [the Millbeck] farmhouse, where travellers can make a good meal of farmhouse fare, there is one thing to be done without doubt; – to visit Dungeon Ghyll. . . . Strangers who arrive untired generally go to the Ghyll while their ham and eggs are preparing” (146).</span></div></div> Fine day on the whole but with showers – Langdale pike seen through a veil of mist.</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 26<sup>th</sup> May</span><br/> Dined with the Party at Brummar Head. Poor Marys tooth drawn. I at Easedale Tarn <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note102" id="Note102_return"><sup class="super">
            (102)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Brimmer Head is on the outskirts of Grasmere on the way to Easedale Tarn, a picturesque pond two miles northwest of the village. </span></div></div> with Miss Cookson.</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 27<sup>th</sup></span><br/> At <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Troutbeck">Troutbeck</a> &amp; Bowness. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note103" id="Note103_return"><sup class="super">
            (103)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Town on the east shore of Windermere known partly for its ferry landing. </span></div></div> Cold air, very bright. Rain comes on, &amp; Snow on the Mountains</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday May 28<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Mr Cookson dines here – young ones stay –. Fine moonlight – a little rain in afternoon</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 29<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Air cold – fine morning. Rain in afternoon. Walk with Miss Cookson in Garden &amp; on West Terrace. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note104" id="Note104_return"><sup class="super">
            (104)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The “Far Terrace” at the western-most edge of the Rydal Mount property. </span></div></div> Fine moonlight night – moon on River.</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 30<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Mrs Smith <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note105" id="Note105_return"><sup class="super">
            (105)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>WW and DW’s second cousin Mary Wordsworth Smith (1780–1867), the older sister of Dorothy Wordsworth Harrison. After her first husband, Capt. William Peake, died in combat in 1813, she married William Proctor Smith (Letters, 5:111n). In 1829 DW would note, “Mrs. Smith – She is Cousin Dorothy’s Sister, and like Dorothy in sweetness of temper etc., but has had the advantage of being much in good company, and has a stronger understanding” (Letters, 5:128).</span></div></div> arrives [–] finest day – I with Miss Cookson over hills &amp; to Skelwyth Fold <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note106" id="Note106_return"><sup class="super">
            (106)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Skelwith Fold is four miles south of Rydal via the route they took, which had them ascending Loughrigg and then crossing Skelwith Bridge. </span></div></div> – Mrs S[mith] here on return.</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 31<sup>st</sup></span><br/> Ladies depart. Still very fine weat her, bright yet cool – With Mrs S[mith] &amp; Miss C[ookson] to Ambleside. Ladies depart, <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note107" id="Note107_return"><sup class="super">
            (107)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Maria Jewsbury and the younger Elizabeth Cookson.</span></div></div> much regretted – Party to Tea – various walks in fields &amp;c. <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Harrison">Mrs Harrison</a> &amp; party, to Tea – fine moonlight on Windermere</p></div></section><section class="section" id="index.xml-body.1_div.9"><header><h1><span style="font-size: 75%">[June 1825]</span></h1></header><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday June 1<sup>st</sup></span><br/> Very wet morning. Mrs Smith departs – all day rain[.] In evening, walked with W to Ambleside [–] very wet. Again began with Dante this morning</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 2<sup>nd</sup></span><br/> Great flood – – Walk to <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Fox">Fox Ghyll</a> and <a class="link_ref" href="Ghyll">Fox Ghyll</a> – D[ora] to <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Longdale">Langdale</a> frightened a little by the high water. I walked to Ambleside after tea – – to seek lodgings for Miss D. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note108" id="Note108_return"><sup class="super">
            (108)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Likely not one of the Dowlings (who already lived in Ambleside) but the Miss Dawson mentioned in the 22 and 27 June entries.</span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 3<sup>rd</sup></span><br/> – Showery – went with M to Water head <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note109" id="Note109_return"><sup class="super">
            (109)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The northern tip of Windermere, just east of Brathay.</span></div></div> &amp; <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Brathay">Brathay</a>. Met <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Jackson">Wm Jackson</a> – &amp; <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Dorothy">Cousin D[orothy]</a> &amp;c. – Dora at <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Keswick">Keswick</a> – – Young party with Willy at <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Robinson">Mr Robinson’s</a></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday June 4<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Very heavy showers. Called on Webbers, <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note110" id="Note110_return"><sup class="super">
            (110)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Apparently temporary residents of Rydal. Dora reported on 28 May 1825, “The Webbers’ Servants come on Monday and themselves on Wednesday. They must be Grandees for Mrs W said in a note to Margarite ‘I shall send over the Butler to order in coals etc.’” (Letters, 4:352).</span></div></div> <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Harrison">Harrisons</a>, <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Scambler">Mrs Scambler</a> [,] <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Carr">Mrs Carr</a> – Wm J[ackson] to tea. Reading Excursion <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note111" id="Note111_return"><sup class="super">
            (111)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>WW had begun revising the version of this book-length poem he had published in 1814. On 28 May, DW reported that WW and MW “have had a hard tug at the Excursion, and have gone through with it. [DW] begin[s] tomorrow to read it over” (Letters, 4:354).</span></div></div></p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday June 5<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Rainy morning, clears in afternoon – Harrisons to Tea.</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday</span> – Cold but fair. D. rode to <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Kendal">Kendal</a>. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note112" id="Note112_return"><sup class="super">
            (112)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Visiting the Cooksons, to whose children, especially Elizabeth, Dora was quite close.</span></div></div> Rainy evening – Tea at <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Campbell">Col. Campbell’s</a></p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 7<sup>th</sup> June</span><br/> Mr Jackson dined here – unpacking Tea &amp;c</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 8</span><br/> Unpacking again. M busy with curtains. I at Ambleside. – Wet night [–] could not go to <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Knott">Miss Knotts</a></p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 9<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Very fine bright day. On Nab Scar <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note113" id="Note113_return"><sup class="super">
            (113)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>See note for 2 December 1824 entry.</span></div></div> with Miss Yarker. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note114" id="Note114_return"><sup class="super">
            (114)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Likely Sarah Yarker (b. 1806), eldest daughter of Joseph Yarker, a customs collector from Ulverston (see note for 6 July entry). </span></div></div> Webbers[,] Mr Maltby, <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note115" id="Note115_return"><sup class="super">
            (115)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Likely either Rev. Edward Maltby (1770–1859, DNB), Mrs. Elliott’s only surviving brother, or one of his elder sons. The clergyman’s first wife, Mary, had just passed away in early May.</span></div></div> Mr B[enson] H[arrison], <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Barlow">Miss Barlow</a>, Mr Fraser <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note116" id="Note116_return"><sup class="super">
            (116)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Possibly Rev. Lionel Fraser (1807–1833), whom WW would later describe as a young friend of his from Peterhouse, Cambridge (Letters, 5:651). He may therefore have been staying with Tillbrooke, a fellow at Peterhouse.</span></div></div> to Tea.</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 10<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Fine warm day – [calls?] [Shirts?]. Bamford <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note117" id="Note117_return"><sup class="super">
            (117)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Robert W. Bamford, an inspector of schools near Durham who had taught John at the Grasmere school in 1812 (Letters, 3:7). WW had corresponded with Bamford as recently as 28 May (Letters, 4:349).</span></div></div> calls – Read Excursion <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note118" id="Note118_return"><sup class="super">
            (118)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>See note for 4 June entry.</span></div></div> out of doors[.] Letter from Mr R <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note119" id="Note119_return"><sup class="super">
            (119)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Henry Crabb Robinson (1775–1867, DNB), a close friend and regular correspondent with whom the Wordsworths explored the Continent in 1820 and hoped to take further excursions in the years ahead. DW responded to this letter from Robinson on 2 July (Letters, 4:372).</span></div></div> – D returning from Kendal. – Mrs Carr to tea. Supper with <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Luff">Mrs Luff</a></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 11<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Lovely Day – with Wm. at Thompsons in Langdale Powder Mills <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note120" id="Note120_return"><sup class="super">
            (120)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>According to Industrial History of Cumbria, a gunpowder manufactory had opened near Elterwater in Langdale in 1824.</span></div></div> – <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Loughrigg">Loughrigg</a></p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 12<sup>th</sup></span> – very hot [–] dined at Mr Robinsons. – Cold caught with heat in Langdale. To bed at 8. All this week, hot &amp; splendid weather [all?]</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 15<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Now going to Kendal. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note121" id="Note121_return"><sup class="super">
            (121)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>On 2 July, DW mentioned having recently spent a week in Kendal with the ailing Miss Cookson (Letters, 4:372).</span></div></div> Very bright hot weather till Monday – then cold &amp; dry after a little Rain on [Sunday?] night –</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday </span>– went with <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Cookson">Mrs C[ookson]</a> to Helsing &amp; Levens Park – home by Canal <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note122" id="Note122_return"><sup class="super">
            (122)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The village of Helsington is seven miles south of the Cooksons’ home in Staveley, and Levens Hall is two miles farther south. The Lancaster-to-Kendal Canal by which they returned opened in 1819. </span></div></div> – Lovely night</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday</span> – to Burton with James <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note123" id="Note123_return"><sup class="super">
            (123)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Burton-in-Kendal, on the southern border of Cumberland, is 16 miles south of Staveley. James was the Cooksons’ 21-year-old son. </span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday </span>to Hawes Bridge <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note124" id="Note124_return"><sup class="super">
            (124)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>A picturesque crossing of the River Kent on the southern outskirts of Kendal (eight miles south of Staveley). </span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p>– and <span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday the 21<sup>st</sup> of June</span> – <br/> came home with James – Cold &amp; rather gloomy – walked thro’ my Lady’s Woods. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note125" id="Note125_return"><sup class="super">
            (125)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The context suggests they had taken the liberty of passing through the woods of Rydal Hall, perhaps because Lady Ann le Fleming was not in residence (Letters, 4:370). Alternately, this could refer to Lady Wood, the field west of White Moss.</span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 22<sup>nd</sup></span><br/> To Ambleside with James – cold &amp; threatening Rain. Called on Miss Dawson, <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note126" id="Note126_return"><sup class="super">
            (126)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Unidentified but possibly a relative of Eliza Dawson Fletcher (see note for 28 June entry). DW’s referencing her as “Miss Dawson” rather than by her first name suggests she was not one of the laboring-class Dawsons whom the Wordsworths had employed. </span></div></div> – &amp; Mrs Luff, &amp; again at night at Ambleside. John arrived from Oxford disappointed of Sara – <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note127" id="Note127_return"><sup class="super">
            (127)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>John and SH’s original plan to travel northward together was nixed by her needing to extend her stay with Tom and Mary Hutchinson (Letters, 4:374; SH, 305).</span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 23<sup>rd</sup></span><br/> Packet from Lancaster, all morning reading it <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note128" id="Note128_return"><sup class="super">
            (128)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Unclear but, given her describing reading it as a “job,” perhaps papers related to WW’s duties as Distributor of Stamps. </span></div></div> – &amp; other jobs – Sunny but cold [–] sate under Crags – Frenchman <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note129" id="Note129_return"><sup class="super">
            (129)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Unidentified.</span></div></div> called &amp; <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Watson">the Watsons.</a></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 24<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Wrote various letters[.] D. <span style="text-decoration:underline">was</span> to have come from the Wood <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note130" id="Note130_return"><sup class="super">
            (130)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The Barlows’ home in Troutbeck.</span></div></div> – a Rainy afternoon keeps her. It is very cold &amp; dark – now at 9 o’clock – tired with letter-writing – Miss J, Sara, Miss Cookson, Mrs Johnson[,] Miss Barker &amp;c – <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note131" id="Note131_return"><sup class="super">
            (131)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The first three listed correspondents are Maria Jewsbury, SH, and Miss Elizabeth Cookson. The fourth is likely Mrs. James Johnson of Kendal, of whom DW reported on 13 February, “A fortnight ago, poor Mrs J. on discovering that Mr. J had paid attentions not very delicate to her cook left the house with her 3 children” (Letters, 4:317). The last correspondent was Mary Barker, the old friend with whom DW made her “Excursion up Scafell Pike” in 1818 and who had since moved to France.</span></div></div></p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 25 </span>– Letter from Miss B[arker]. Showery. D comes home – sunny gleams – –</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 26<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Cold &amp; showery. At Mrs Carrs to Tea, with Carlyles’ <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note132" id="Note132_return"><sup class="super">
            (132)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Perhaps the family of Robert Carlyle, an artist who based a number of prints and a five-canto romance (De Vaux; Or, the Heir of Gilsland [1817]) on his native Carlisle. In October 1825, MW forwarded some “Cumberland news” gleaned from a “Miss Carlysle” (LMW, 123), and in 1831 WW wrote a Miss Carlyle of Carlisle inquiring about lodging options there for Willy (Letters, 5:416).</span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 27<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Fine day. Carlyles call &amp; Miss Dawson. On <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Loughrigg">Loughrigg Fell</a> with W. Langdale pikes like a Tall mountain <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note133" id="Note133_return"><sup class="super">
            (133)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>That is, WW and DW gazed westward from the top of Loughrigg at the Langdale Pikes. </span></div></div> – very fine – moon – but cloudy.</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 28<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Miss Carlyle to dinner [–] walk &amp; Fletchers <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note134" id="Note134_return"><sup class="super">
            (134)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Possibly the Edinburgh philanthropist and early WW enthusiast Eliza Fletcher (1770–1858, DNB) and her attorney husband, Archibald Fletcher (1746–1828, DNB), who had met the Wordsworths through their common friends, the Hardens, in 1806. After her husband’s death, Mrs. Fletcher often holidayed in the Lakes before permanently moving to Thorney How in Grasmere in 1841 (Fletcher, Autobiography, 78, 89, 212–14, 221, 249).</span></div></div> – home with her at night. D poorly – brought [home?] medicine, &amp; drowsy [–] clear sky[,] vapours rise</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 29</span><br/> Still cold. Henry H <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note135" id="Note135_return"><sup class="super">
            (135)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Henry Hutchinson, the 55-year-old bachelor brother of MW and SH who settled on the Isle of Man after a career as a sailor. </span></div></div> arrives – showery – walk to Fox Ghyll, call on Miss King <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note136" id="Note136_return"><sup class="super">
            (136)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>An old acquaintance of Mrs. Luff, dating to at least the early 1810s (Letters, 3:126).</span></div></div></p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday <span style="text-decoration: line-through">30<sup>th</sup></span> 31<sup>st</sup></span><br/> Mrs Luff &amp; Miss K[ing] at Kendal. Fine day, but a shower or Two. – Tea at Mrs Campbell’s with Miss Dawson</p></section><section class="section" id="index.xml-body.1_div.10"><header><h1><span style="font-size: 75%">[July 1825]</span></h1></header><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 1<sup>st</sup> July</span><br/> Very fine day – Carlyles at Langdale. – Hay strewn &amp; shorn <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note137" id="Note137_return"><sup class="super">
            (137)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>See 4 July entry and other accounts of haymaking in LDW, 60; LMW, 92; and LSH, 240.</span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday</span><br/> Lovely day – Walk on <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Loughrigg">Loughrigh</a> with Henry H[utchinson] after dinner. Fright with the Cow <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note138" id="Note138_return"><sup class="super">
            (138)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Aggressive cows had been a perpetual source of fear since the GJ years. On 2 February 1802, DW confessed, “Every horned cow puts me in terror” (62); and on 10 June 1802, she reported Coleridge’s having “been attacked by a Cow” en route to Grasmere (108).</span></div></div> – very warm. Let fire out.</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday July 3<sup>rd</sup></span><br/> Fine day – not so warm – fine after Tea – Carlyles call [–] to Church –</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 4<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Fine day very busy – hay in – Made curtains for D’s bed. <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Carr">Mr Carr’s</a> after Tea.</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 5<sup>th</sup></span> <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note139" id="Note139_return"><sup class="super">
            (139)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The first of four unusually detailed entries that chronicle DW’s four-day excursion to and from Kents Bank (23 miles south of Rydal on the southeast coast of the Cartmel Peninsula). The traveling party for the outward journey seems to have included DW, WW, MW, Mrs. Luff, Miss Dowling, and Miss Woodville, with at least MW and WW staying behind at Kents Bank for a family holiday. </span></div></div> <br/> – At ½ past 10 set off in Cart to Coniston <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note140" id="Note140_return"><sup class="super">
            (140)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Village eight miles southwest of Rydal at the northwest tip of Coniston Water. From there, as DW explains, the party hired a boat to sail down the lake. </span></div></div> – took up M. at <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Luff">Mrs Luff’s</a> – <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Dowling">Miss E[liza] Dowling</a> &amp; Miss Woodville <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note141" id="Note141_return"><sup class="super">
            (141)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Unidentified. Possibly a fellow teacher or a student from the Dowlings’ school. </span></div></div> in Road – cool, &amp; rather dull – sun breaks out, fine lights on hills – . – I walked from Church Coniston. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note142" id="Note142_return"><sup class="super">
            (142)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>St. Andrew’s Church, completed in 1819 to replace Coniston’s sixteenth-century chapel. </span></div></div> The rest in cart – . – Met Mr H <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note143" id="Note143_return"><sup class="super">
            (143)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Henry Hutchinson met them in Coniston to guide them to his summer rental home on the lake. </span></div></div> in field, despairing of us &amp; going to set off to Torver. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note144" id="Note144_return"><sup class="super">
            (144)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Hamlet two and a half miles south of Coniston along Coniston Water’s western shore. </span></div></div> Dined in Boat – –. Middle of Lake least interesting – but in lower part, right shore very pleasing – varied with little rocks. Banks &amp; wood – – Party waiting at Mr H’s summer house – Enchanting view up Lake – &amp; backwards to the foot – – like a little peaceful soft lake – with verdant fields – farm house, hay makers. Standing on Mr H’s Rocky peninsula (cut into an Island) <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note145" id="Note145_return"><sup class="super">
            (145)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Hutchinson’s rental appears to have been on Fir’s Island (also known as Knott’s Island), midway along the eastern shore of Coniston Water. An island when the lake is high, it becomes a peninsula when the water recedes. </span></div></div> – thought of Trossachs – &amp; compared the contrasts here to those between Lochs Katherine &amp; Vennache <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note146" id="Note146_return"><sup class="super">
            (146)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Lochs Katrine and Venachar are both in the Trossachs, the mountainous region in central Scotland that DW first visited in 1803 and described in detail in Journal of My Second Tour of Scotland (1822).</span></div></div> – pleasant Ride to Ulverston. Thro’ firlets <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note147" id="Note147_return"><sup class="super">
            (147)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Apparently DW’s coinage.</span></div></div> – woody peopled valley – River Crake – Iron foundry – Mr Penny’s house (Mr Machael’s – Penny Bridge). <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note148" id="Note148_return"><sup class="super">
            (148)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Ulverston is a major market town near the head of the Furness Peninsula. The nine-mile southward journey that DW’s party made that afternoon and evening from Fir’s Island to Ulverston followed the River Crake from the foot of Coniston Water through the Crake Valley, past the iron foundries at Nibthwaite and Penny Bridge, and on to Penny Bridge Hall. As DW’s shorthand account suggests, upon William Penny’s death in 1788, Penny Bridge Hall had descended to his son-in-law, James Machell (Bardsley, Chronicles of the Town, 118).</span></div></div> Noble oaks darkening sand – fine trees – rich meadows. Reach Lund between 7 &amp; 8 – hospitality of old Mrs Harrison – 13 Gd children. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note149" id="Note149_return"><sup class="super">
            (149)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Located on Ulverston’s eastern edge, “The Lund” was the hereditary estate of Benson Harrison, the new husband of DW’s cousin (see note for 31 May entry). Benson’s mother, “Old Mrs. Harrison,” was widowed in 1820 but apparently still presided at The Lund. With Benson being her only son, and possibly her only child, DW’s mention of “13 Gd. Children” may refer to godchildren rather than grandchildren. </span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 6<sup>th</sup></span> <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note150" id="Note150_return"><sup class="super">
            (150)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>On Day 2 of their trip, the party remained in the vicinity of Ulverston, confining their exploring to a six-mile round-trip excursion to Conishead Priory. </span></div></div> <br/> All walk to Priory grounds <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note151" id="Note151_return"><sup class="super">
            (151)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Conishead Priory, two and a half miles south of Ulverston near the Furness Peninsula’s eastern shore, was the site of a twelfth-century monastery, remnants of which had been razed in 1821 to make way for the modern buildings DW describes. </span></div></div> – – fine trees – long walks in grassy hollow. – Winter more agreeable here – Huntsmans Lodge <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note152" id="Note152_return"><sup class="super">
            (152)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Possibly Bardsea Hall (destroyed 1927), neighboring Conishead Priory to the south, which Lord Molyneux converted into a hunting lodge in the early eighteenth century. </span></div></div> – deep deep gloom – [a little?] shrouded – silver crescent horns – revealing form &amp; notion of the dark bodies of the [ ] – unintelligible building – – Conservatory Chapel rich <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note153" id="Note153_return"><sup class="super">
            (153)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>In 1830, Sir Edward Baines remarked that the new “conservatory of plants” Philip William Wyatt had designed at Conishead Priory “is tastefully constructed; its rich Gothic windows, with stained glass, and the ivy which covers the front, give it the appearance of a chapel” (Companion, 232).</span></div></div> – one part Flemish, but not so rich – another gothist – 2 fine Flemish Chimneys – on a wee wee Building out of taste – – Charming refreshment on shore – sit &amp; [ ] – party with [ ] &amp;c. Discover little Brook – travelling through the sands whose Birth place we had marked, &amp; its girdle of water-plants – – Ulverston Church <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note154" id="Note154_return"><sup class="super">
            (154)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>St. Mary’s, Ulverston’s ancient parish church.</span></div></div> very [ ] – home thro hot Lanes –. Party in the evening – Wm and I to Ulverston with Mrs Ireland <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note155" id="Note155_return"><sup class="super">
            (155)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Probably Nancy Wordsworth Ireland, DW and WW’s cousin and Dorothy Harrison’s sister, who in the early 1810s had married a Rev. G. Ireland (Letters, 3:161).</span></div></div> and Miss Yarker –. Mrs Y. in bad health <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note156" id="Note156_return"><sup class="super">
            (156)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Likely referencing the family of Joseph Yarker (1764–1843), squire of Dykelands and royal customs collector for Ulverston. If so, the “Miss Yarker” here and in DW’s entry for 6 June would presumably be Joseph’s eldest daughter, Sarah Jane (b. 1806); “Mrs. Y” his wife, Margaret (b. 1786); and the “busy daughters” his unmarried younger daughters, Ann, Mary, and Margaret. Although none of the Yarkers are mentioned in the Wordsworths’ surviving letters, the Rydal Mount Visitors Book records the “Misses Yarker” of Ulverston visiting in 1836, 1838, and 1839 (DCMS 166, pp. 45, 55, 60, and 68).</span></div></div> – her busy daughters [sitting?] with her – Dismal visit to Mrs. B. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note157" id="Note157_return"><sup class="super">
            (157)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Unidentified.</span></div></div> Tears and lamentation – melancholy old age.</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 7<sup>th</sup></span> <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note158" id="Note158_return"><sup class="super">
            (158)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>DW’s intrepid Day 3 itinerary included a 10-mile coach ride along the Furness Peninsula’s eastern edge from Ulverston to Piel Island; a boat trip across the Leven estuary to the Cartmel Sands; a four-mile walk across the Cartmel Peninsula to Kents Bank; and, in the late afternoon and evening, an eight-mile hike northward from Kents Bank to Newby Bridge, where she lodged for the night. </span></div></div> – Rose at 6. Departed from Lund at ½ past 7. Waited with Mrs H[arrison] for Coach – Only one inside one out place. – Lovely morning – Lights on hills[,] clear air. – Mountains very grand – verdant spots below – – Wheels through deep water seeming not to move [–] silver streaky water, dull golden sands – – Piel Castle <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note159" id="Note159_return"><sup class="super">
            (159)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>A fourteenth-century fortress on Piel Island built by the monks of Furness Abbey to protect the peninsula from attack by sea. For the Wordsworths, it had particular associations, as George Beaumont’s painting of the castle inspired the “Elegiac Stanzas” WW wrote upon the 1805 death of his and DW’s brother John. </span></div></div> – [Sailor?] in Coach – heard Crash &amp; saw fall of part of ruin – – Land at Webster’s (Quarry Flat) <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note160" id="Note160_return"><sup class="super">
            (160)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Quarry Flat, an old sandstone mine along the Cartmel Sands and the ancestral home of the pioneering Cumbrian architects Francis Webster (1767–1827) and his son George (1797–1864, DNB). There is no evidence the Wordsworths knew Francis, but they likely met George, the region’s most celebrated young architect, while he worked on Rydal Chapel (one of his first major commissions). For the Websters’ roots at Quarry Flat, see Rigge, “Harrington Tomb.”</span></div></div> – house unpromising – no view – closed up windows – very neat kitchen – kind woman – but saw at once in no state for us – Friendly talk. Cloth spread for new butter &amp; churn milk – refused, &amp; went on – – Lad called from gazing thro prospect glass <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note161" id="Note161_return"><sup class="super">
            (161)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>A hand telescope.</span></div></div> to guide us to Holker. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note162" id="Note162_return"><sup class="super">
            (162)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Immediately northwest of Quarry Flat, this stately home and gardens has been in the Cavendish family since the late eighteenth century. </span></div></div> – – Delightful park, old place pretty, under hills – Large but not handsome white house. – Two noble sycamores in front – – &amp; one other shorn like a Bush at top – very large – civil house-keeper <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note163" id="Note163_return"><sup class="super">
            (163)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>When the owners were not in residence, housekeepers at grand homes were often permitted to offer tours to genteel visitors. </span></div></div> –. Finest pictures gone – – 1 Claude not fine left – – Sir Peter Lely’s Ladies – – &amp; other portraits &amp; pretty little Landscapes a few. Head of John Bunyan <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note164" id="Note164_return"><sup class="super">
            (164)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Much of Holker Hall’s impressive art collection, including the Bunyan portrait DW mentions, was lost in an 1871 fire. Among the rescued works were Sir Peter Lely’s Lady Cleveland in Mourning and two of the family’s four paintings by Claude Lorraine (or “Claudes”). See Stockdale, Annales Caermoelenses, 424–32.</span></div></div> – – Thence to Cark – Dusty hot vulgar Village – then Flukborough the [inn?] (called at Inn arranged about water.) <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note165" id="Note165_return"><sup class="super">
            (165)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>In the manuscript, this aside comes in a footnote, the only such note in Notebook 1 (see fig. 2). Parentheses are added here for readability. </span></div></div> – – on to Allisthwaite <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note166" id="Note166_return"><sup class="super">
            (166)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>From Holker Hall, the party traveled one and a half miles south through the village of Cark and on to the inn at Flookburgh. From there they headed east for three miles to Allithwaite. </span></div></div> in pretty dell – Ivied wall – 2 old halls, one with a turret or burl. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note167" id="Note167_return"><sup class="super">
            (167)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The two halls are Boarbank Hall and Wraysholme Tower, the latter a fifteenth-century fortress with multiple turrets. A burl is a bump or protuberance. </span></div></div> Climb hill to [Mortal Man?] – – – Thence on to Kents Bank but turn aside, to prospect hill – Turret – descend to Kents Bank – Charming hill. – Flowers turf – sheep [–] stones worn away – – through little orchard – civil men – Call at Inn – Taken lodgings. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note168" id="Note168_return"><sup class="super">
            (168)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The parodic Kent’s Bank Mercury produced by Dora and Jewsbury indicates that, while the Wordsworths stayed in the coastal cottage of their acquaintance William Ashburner, others in their party were “compelled to take up their lodgings in the adjoining Hotel” (WLMS A / Jewsbury, Maria Jane / 52).</span></div></div> Dine – – On to Grange – charming Italian scenery – pretty houses[,] gardens. Elder Bushes – – Liddle pretty village in dell. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note169" id="Note169_return"><sup class="super">
            (169)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The village of Grange-over-Sands is two miles up the coast from Kents Bank. From there, Lindale is two miles inland to the north. </span></div></div> Discovered chapel – – embosomed in Trees, but before this a fine view – – from hill, over sands, &amp; Castle head <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note170" id="Note170_return"><sup class="super">
            (170)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>A Georgian-style country house built in 1778 for the industrialist John Wilkinson. </span></div></div> discovered on plain – woody mount, pleasure paths. Think of Belagio. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note171" id="Note171_return"><sup class="super">
            (171)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Bellagio, the picturesque Italian resort on Lake Como, which DW saw in 1820. </span></div></div> A little way from Liddle discover well on side of road –. Entrance arched, rather lintelled over with old ash stem – – Roof arched with stone – green with moss ... Ivy with Adder’s Tongue fern <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note172" id="Note172_return"><sup class="super">
            (172)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>A variety of fern so named because its stalk resembles a snake’s tongue. It survives as an underground rhizome nine months of the year, appearing above the surface only during the summer. </span></div></div> &amp; Geranium – descend [by?] steps – 8 – broken with age – 3 niches. What [gent?] has this been dedicated – Inquire of woman – – never noticed it – of Boys – Oh yes! – What do they call it[,] what name has it[?] Oh! it’s Dicky [Greyson?] well .... Why so? – Perhaps he [named?] it. Does he live there now? Nay he’s sellt up. It must be very auld. Ay, says Boy I remember it a long time – (he not more than 16) – Companion Rolling in Dust like an ass of the desart – [On?] &amp; [ ] [ ] – On through woody valley; [hut?] on side of hill – – Still woody country – Parts very populous. Farm houses picturesque[.] Reach Newby Bridge about 8. After Tea strolled up &amp; down River – the dark figure of an Angler standing on the slippery slope of the Weir <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note173" id="Note173_return"><sup class="super">
            (173)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>A barrier or dam in a river.</span></div></div> – that with its whiteness brought out the lower part of the man’s figure – Could not see the pipe in his mouth, but discovered that he was smoking, by a thin small volume of vapour in the air, which was faintly reflected in the smooth water above the Weir – Soon to bed &amp; paid Bill intending to rise early. – Charge for both 3/6 – &amp; very much obliged for a Shilling over –</p></div><figure class="figure"><img src="placeholder.png" alt="Figure 2: Portion of the 7 July 1825 entry in DCMS 104.1" class="inline" style=" width:400px;"/></figure><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday July 8<sup>th</sup></span> <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note174" id="Note174_return"><sup class="super">
            (174)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Day 4 began with a seven-mile early morning hike from Newby Bridge to Far Sawrey along Windermere’s western shore. From there DW took the Windermere ferry to Bowness, walked two and a half miles to Troutbeck for breakfast with the Barlows, and then traveled five miles on foot to arrive at Rydal Mount in the late afternoon. She never specifies whether she was accompanied by others on this return leg of the trip.</span></div></div> <br/> A very fine morning –. Rose at ½ past 4 – off at 5 minutes past 5 – Returned to seek W’s glove – Shady cool lane – – House to Right (supposed Mr Townley’s) a naked-yellow Front, <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note175" id="Note175_return"><sup class="super">
            (175)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Naked as in bare or devoid of shrubbery. DW seems to be looking across the narrow southern tip of Windermere toward Town Head, the recently renovated estate of William Townley, High Sheriff of Lancashire. </span></div></div> &amp; hugged in on each side, by choked up plantations <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note176" id="Note176_return"><sup class="super">
            (176)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Apparently, a sidelong allusion to the massive larch plantation the late Richard Watson had established above Town Head on Gummer’s How. Since 1810, WW had vehemently denounced such “vegetable manufactories” in successive editions of hisGuide to the Lakes.</span></div></div> – pretty green prospect – white church on the hill – among coppice woods – – – Stock Park &amp; Mr Lowthwaites <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note177" id="Note177_return"><sup class="super">
            (177)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>DW slightly misremembers both names. In his Tourist’s New Guide, William Green clarifies that Stott (not Stock) Park was “late the seat of George Braithwaite, Esq., but now the residence of his sisters” (1:197).</span></div></div> – Low under Woods … Fine &amp; numerous yew trees on the steeps near Stock Park – Low Graithwaite\ <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note178" id="Note178_return"><sup class="super">
            (178)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Green lists “Abraham Rawlinson, Esq., a minor” as the owner of Low Graithwaite, noting that Graithwaite is where “the ferry and Hawkshead roads unite” (1:197). </span></div></div> in style of Rydal Mount. Fine Larches – &amp; other fine trees. But all hereabouts buried &amp; chill with woods &amp; Mr Sands’s worst of all – Spoiled plantations. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note179" id="Note179_return"><sup class="super">
            (179)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Miles Sandys, then the squire of High Graithwaite, had followed Watson’s lead in investing in larch plantations on his property near Windermere. DW’s complaint about this specific plantation echoes a remark WW inserted into his Guide to the Lakes in 1822 about how “the view from the Pleasure-house of the Station near the [Windermere] Ferry has suffered much from Larch plantations” (138).</span></div></div> Dull traveling compared with the cottaged &amp; farm-housed valley last night. Many woods, all belonging to Gentlemen. Noble view after Graithwaite – Storrs’ Clock strikes 7 <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note180" id="Note180_return"><sup class="super">
            (180)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>From the opposite shore of Windermere, DW appears to have heard the bell of St. Martin’s, the parish church just north of Storrs Hall. </span></div></div> – – Ferried over Lake. When I observed to Boatsman that all the Land was divided among the Gentry, &amp; that it was more chearful, when scattered over with houses, he replied “Aye it is more christian-like – Its like a wilderness” – “a genteel wilderness” says Wm –. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note181" id="Note181_return"><sup class="super">
            (181)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Presumably a remark from conversation, as this phrase does not appear in WW’s published works. </span></div></div> At <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Barlow">Mrs Barlow’s</a> at 10 [–] Breakfast &amp; Luncheon <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note182" id="Note182_return"><sup class="super">
            (182)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>While breakfast would have been a full meal, luncheon was more of a light repast a few hours before the mid-afternoon dinner. </span></div></div> – home at 4 with Miss B[arlow] – – wrote to <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Jewsbury">Miss J[ewsbury]</a>, to Mary –</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday – 9<sup>th</sup> July.</span><br/> Very hot – &amp; bright. Wrote to <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Sarah">Mrs Coleridge</a> and <a class="link_ref" href="Coleridge">Mrs Coleridge</a> – – Sought speakings <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note183" id="Note183_return"><sup class="super">
            (183)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Passages from literary texts that one memorized or recited. </span></div></div> two hours – – –. Read Madam Genlis. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note184" id="Note184_return"><sup class="super">
            (184)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>First published in English translation in early 1825, Memoirs of the Countess de Genlis attracted a wide English readership with its vivid accounts of the atrocities of the French Revolution and the aristocratic debauchery that preceded it. Writing H. C. Robinson on 2 July, DW exuded, “I am deep in Madame de Genlis’s life – a hundred times more entertaining than the best of our now-a-days novels – and how much more surprizing!” (Letters, 4:375).</span></div></div> Made wine –. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note185" id="Note185_return"><sup class="super">
            (185)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Cf. entries from 3, 4, and 10 December 1824. </span></div></div> Wm at Tea at Mr Webber’s. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note186" id="Note186_return"><sup class="super">
            (186)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>See note for 4 June.</span></div></div> They called in morning.</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 10<sup>th</sup></span> – Very hot. Thunder storm in church &amp; flood. – <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Barlow">Barlows</a> &amp; Miss Dawson <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note187" id="Note187_return"><sup class="super">
            (187)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>See note for 22 June.</span></div></div> to dinner. Mr Wilkinson &amp; mother <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note188" id="Note188_return"><sup class="super">
            (188)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Most likely “Lakers” who called while traveling through the region, not the abolitionist Thomas Wilkinson(who was too old to have a living mother) or the artist Joseph Wilkinson (who fell out of contact with WW after 1810).</span></div></div> to Tea &amp; all night. Dora very poorly.</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 11<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Fine day, but still thundery. To Ambleside with Wilkinsons – Odd jobs for D &amp;c. all day, &amp; at night to Ambleside again[.] Tea with Mrs Carr – consult about D – wrote letters</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 12<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Rose at 4. John &amp; D. go to Ulverston. Warm, breezy morning – – cloudy afternoon, threatening of Thunder [–] wrote to Sara, <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Cookson">Mrs Cookson</a>, Mary <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note189" id="Note189_return"><sup class="super">
            (189)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>MW had stayed behind at Kents Bank for a family holiday after arriving there with DW on 7 July. </span></div></div> –. Allan Bank <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note190" id="Note190_return"><sup class="super">
            (190)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Home of the Campbells.</span></div></div> to Tea. Reached home at ¼ before 11. Good news of Dora –.</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 13<sup>th</sup></span><br/> All day heavy rain. Wm at <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Low">Low Wood</a> and <a class="link_ref" href="Wood">Low Wood</a> – [Such?] [ ] – Mr Gould <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note191" id="Note191_return"><sup class="super">
            (191)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Unidentified.</span></div></div> – I walked to Ambleside – Stifled with heat</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 14<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Rainy morning – Clears up – very fine, but sultry[.] Barlows &amp; Mr Bailey <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note192" id="Note192_return"><sup class="super">
            (192)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Likely a brother of Frances Bayley Barlow (see Axon, Family of Bayley, 47–48).</span></div></div> to Tea</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 15<sup>th</sup> July –</span><br/> Fine morning – sunshine but sultry – cloudy afternoon, heavy rain – damage in walks repaired</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 16<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Fine morning – but sultry. Rainy afternoon – – clears beautifully. Lovely Evening. Walk with Wm. on Terrace – Ruby Lights on Lake –</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 17<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Very hot – Barlows – &amp; [pews?] quite full – Mrs Maltby <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note193" id="Note193_return"><sup class="super">
            (193)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>See note for 9 June. Since the future Bishop Maltby had just lost his wife, this may have been a daughter-in-law. </span></div></div> to tea [–] loveliest evening ever seen –</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 18<sup>th</sup></span> clear and intensely hot – packing <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note194" id="Note194_return"><sup class="super">
            (194)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>For the following day’s trip to Kents Bank.</span></div></div> – making Jelly – &amp;c &amp;c. <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#De">Mrs de Quincey</a> and <a class="link_ref" href="Quincey">Mrs de Quincey</a> at night <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note195" id="Note195_return"><sup class="super">
            (195)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Since their lease had ended at Fox Ghyll and Fox Ghyll a few months earlier, Margaret De Quincey and her children had lived with her father at Nab Cottage in Rydal. This entry seems to refute Gittings and Manton’s contention that DW unfeelingly ignored Thomas De Quincey’s 16 July plea to attend to his depressed and possibly suicidal wife until he could return from London (241, 246).</span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 19<sup>th</sup></span> <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note196" id="Note196_return"><sup class="super">
            (196)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Despite having just made the round-trip journey to Kents Bank less than two weeks earlier, DW chose to accompany WW, Dora, and Willy on the start of their six-week summer holiday. At various times the family would be joined by Maria Jewsbury, the Southeys, the Barlows, SH, and several of the Kendal Cooksons. John and DW remained behind at Rydal Mount. Dora and Jewsbury offered a lively account of this holiday in their parodic Kent’s Bank Mercury (WLMS A / Jewsbury, Maria Jane / 52).</span></div></div> – Up, 10 minutes before 4 – off to Kents Bank before 5 – wet meadows, clear air, very hot – At Kents Bank ½ past one –. Dora improved – all but me bathe – unpack, arrange &amp;c &amp;c. To bed after Dinner. Ladies arrive from Lancaster to tea. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note197" id="Note197_return"><sup class="super">
            (197)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Maria Jewsbury among them. Unclear who the others might be. </span></div></div> Climb hill. Mountains hazy – ruffling Breeze – On return heard of a thunder storm at Ambleside &amp; Rydal <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note198" id="Note198_return"><sup class="super">
            (198)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Several days later, signaling that she wrote this entry after returning to Rydal. </span></div></div> – – not a Drop of rain with us at K[ents] B[ank]</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 20<sup>th</sup></span> – very hot – I depart at ½ past 5. – changes to cold – dull and grey – [ ] road. Mrs Barlows past 10, home at 12 <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note199" id="Note199_return"><sup class="super">
            (199)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>By this account, DW made the 23-mile trip from Kents Bank to Rydal in six and a half hours (including, it seems, a brief visit with the Barlows in Troutbeck). </span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 21<sup>st</sup></span><br/> Agreeable coolness. Learned at Mrs Barlows of heavy thunder shower here on Tuesday. Boiling preserves – letter-writing &amp;c all day. Called at Mrs Luff’s, <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Robinson">Mrs R[obinson’]s</a> – John at <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Harden">Mrs Harden’s</a> Dance. Invitation to Wood <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note200" id="Note200_return"><sup class="super">
            (200)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The Wood, home of the Barlows.</span></div></div> before breakfast. <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Jackson">Mr Jackson</a> from Harrowgate <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note201" id="Note201_return"><sup class="super">
            (201)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Harrogate, the spa town north of Leeds.</span></div></div></p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 22<sup>nd</sup></span><br/> Still cool, &amp; clear [–] busy all day – letters, Jelly, &amp; after dinner with Barlows to Grasmere, &amp; walk with John to Ambleside</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 23<sup>rd</sup></span><br/> Jelly – <span style="text-decoration:underline">Beautiful day</span> – Rush-bearing <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note202" id="Note202_return"><sup class="super">
            (202)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The old Westmoreland tradition, still practiced today, of covering church floors with rushes in July. In his Ecclesiastical Sonnets, WW celebrated this practice in the poem Rural Ceremony (No. XXII) (Sonnets, 425n).</span></div></div> – – various letters[.] Mr Yates <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note203" id="Note203_return"><sup class="super">
            (203)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Unidentified.</span></div></div> called.</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 24<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Cool pew – singers removed <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note204" id="Note204_return"><sup class="super">
            (204)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Obscure but possibly connected to the rush-bearing rites. </span></div></div> –. No company but Mrs Luff in afternoon, &amp; J. &amp; I drank tea with her –. Catechism <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note205" id="Note205_return"><sup class="super">
            (205)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Likely studying the catechism, or lessons preparatory to confirmation, included in the Anglican Book of Common Prayer.</span></div></div> &amp;c., &amp; bed at ½ past 10[.] Miss J[ewsbury]’s Gazette <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note206" id="Note206_return"><sup class="super">
            (206)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Presumably reading recent poems by Maria Jewsbury published in the Manchester Gazette.</span></div></div> – Mrs Yates calls again.</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 25<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Same clear delightful heat. John to Kents Bank. Tea with Miss Dawson [–] walk up Stock-gill <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note207" id="Note207_return"><sup class="super">
            (207)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The ravine and waterfall on the edge of Ambleside.</span></div></div> – beauteous Evening. John returns <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note208" id="Note208_return"><sup class="super">
            (208)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>To make the 45-mile round-trip journey to and from Kents Bank in a single day, John must have traveled by horse. </span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 26<sup>th</sup></span><br/> John off to <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Keswick">Keswick</a> – finished preserves – wrote to Mary &amp; Mrs C. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note209" id="Note209_return"><sup class="super">
            (209)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Likely Mrs. Cookson but possibly Sarah Coleridge and Sarah Coleridge.</span></div></div> Letters from Sara. Mr Wm Jackson calls – <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Campbell">Campbells</a> – <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Knott">Miss Knott</a> – go with her past Lords’ Oak. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note210" id="Note210_return"><sup class="super">
            (210)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>A renowned oak growing out of a wall along the road between Rydal and Ambleside. </span></div></div> Meet Robinsons, walk with them. Christening fixed. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note211" id="Note211_return"><sup class="super">
            (211)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>DW’s wording seems to connect this christening to the Robinsons, but their newborn twins, Charles and Charlotte, had already been christened in Grasmere on 5 January 1825. This and the 2 August entry may therefore allude to the rechristening of Henry Wilkinson Cookson (1810–1876, DNB), Thomas and Elizabeth’s sixth son. Henry had been baptized a Unitarian at birth but was rechristened an Anglican on 29 August 1825, presumably to qualify for Cambridge (which until Catholic Emancipation in 1829 admitted only Anglicans).</span></div></div> Loveliest of nights moonlight. Called on Mrs Luff in her Bed-room – past 10</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 27<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Danl. Green called <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note212" id="Note212_return"><sup class="super">
            (212)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Rev. Daniel Green (1798–1829), son of John and Molly Green of Grasmere, had recently graduated from Cambridge and taken clerical orders (Letters, 4:218n6).</span></div></div> – Mr Waterhouse &amp; Mr Hoyle. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note213" id="Note213_return"><sup class="super">
            (213)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Mr. Waterhouse is unidentified; Mr. Hoyle was possibly Rev. Charles Hoyle (1773–1848), vicar of Overton, Wiltshire, and author of the Biblical epics Moses Viewing the Promised Land (1804) and Exodus: An Epic Poem (1807).</span></div></div> Thus occupied &amp; tying preserves <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note214" id="Note214_return"><sup class="super">
            (214)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Tying down a jar’s lid was a common method for sealing preserves. </span></div></div> all the Morning – John from K[eswick], with Barlows to Tea. – Out of doors – Lovely night [–] <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Tillbrooke">Tillbroke</a> arrives <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note215" id="Note215_return"><sup class="super">
            (215)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>With Ivy Cottage and Ivy Cottage temporarily vacant after the Elliotts’ departure, Tillbrooke stayed in his own quarters on this trip. SH reported on 7 August that “Till &amp; his fellow Tutor are at the Ivy Cottage with which he is charmed” (WT MS WLL / Hutchinson, Sara / 2 / 110a).</span></div></div></p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 28<sup>th</sup></span> – Rose at 6 – Mrs Carr called [–] Again the same delightful weather – Col Campbell with party – after call on Tillbroke – Miss Dawson to Tea. Tillbroke &amp; Gentlemen, &amp; Mrs Luff. Walk to Ambleside with Miss D[awson][.] Supper at Mr R[obinson]’s –. Moonlight too warm &amp; pleasant to go to Bed.</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 29<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Shelled pease while Mary was cleaning – Lloyd <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note216" id="Note216_return"><sup class="super">
            (216)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Likely Charles Lloyd (1775–1839, DNB), the poet and philanthropist who, prior to his mental breakdown in 1813, lived with his wife and eight children at Old Brathay near Ambleside. After a brief period in Keswick (LMW, 84), he spent his final years in France. Once part of the Wordsworths’ broader social circle—especially after his sister, Priscilla (1781–1815), married WW and DW’s brother, Christopher—Lloyd rarely interacted with them after the mid-1810s.</span></div></div> called – Tea out of doors with John. Walked to Mrs Luffs with Tillbrook &amp; John. Most beautiful night</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sat. 30<sup>th</sup></span> –</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sund. 31<sup>st</sup></span> – The month closes [ ] the same fine weather. Very hot. Mrs Luff to Tea – various visitors, letters</p></section><section class="section" id="index.xml-body.1_div.11"><header><h1><span style="font-size: 75%">[August 1825]</span></h1></header><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 1<sup>st</sup></span><br/> Still very hot:</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 2<sup>nd</sup></span><br/> Christening-day <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note217" id="Note217_return"><sup class="super">
            (217)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>See note for 26 July entry.</span></div></div> [–] fine [–] showers in morning. Fine afternoon.</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 3<sup>rd</sup></span> – Heavy rain.</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 4</span> Showery</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 5<sup>th</sup></span> – The same – Sara H. arrives <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note218" id="Note218_return"><sup class="super">
            (218)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Returning to Rydal after an absence of over two years, SH wrote on 7 August, “This place is more beautiful than ever, but there is great want of the axe &amp; pruning knife. The Trees have grown so much that we are quite shut out from any prospect” (WT MS WLL / Hutchinson, Sara / 2 / 110a).</span></div></div> – &amp; Mr Parrin. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note219" id="Note219_return"><sup class="super">
            (219)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Likely Robert Perrin, editor of the Carlisle Patriot (see Letters, 4:460, 469).</span></div></div> John goes to the Balloon. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note220" id="Note220_return"><sup class="super">
            (220)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>On 5 August, thousands flocked to Kendal Castle for a highly anticipated balloon launch by Charles Green, England’s foremost aeronaut. By noon, though, the flight had been canceled because of a slight wind, leading the WG to decry the entire event as a hoax (The Balloon!!!, 6 August 1825).</span></div></div></p></div></section><section class="section" id="index.xml-body.1_div.12"><header><h1><span style="font-size: 75%">[Jumps two months to October 1825]</span></h1></header><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday, October 7<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Since the day of Sara Hutchinson’s arrival (August 5<sup>th</sup>), I have not written a word. – Weather was then broken. – Mrs Hutchinson <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note221" id="Note221_return"><sup class="super">
            (221)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Mary Hutchinson, wife of MW and SH’s brother Tom, who was traveling to recover her health and to be away from Brinsop during a major renovation. She would spend a month at Rydal before going with MW to Harrogate, the spa town near Leeds (Letters, 4:392).</span></div></div> and the party came from Kent’s Bank on Monday, 15<sup>th </sup>August – A few days of cold weather. Afterwards very fine &amp; very hot – for some time – Consecration &amp;c &amp;c <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note222" id="Note222_return"><sup class="super">
            (222)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Eight months after its opening (see 25 December 1824 entry), the chapel of St. Mary in Rydal was consecrated on 27 August by the Bishop of Chester. Anticipating this major event, SH wrote on 7 August, “We are to have grand doings at the consecration on the 27th” (WT MS WLL / Hutchinson, Sara / 2 / 110a). SH provided additional details on both the consecration and Sir Walter Scott’s visit (see following note) in her sketch diary for early August (WT MS WLMS H / 1 / 6 / 2).</span></div></div> – Mr Canning[,] Sir Walter Scott <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note223" id="Note223_return"><sup class="super">
            (223)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>In late August, John Bolton, a wealthy Liverpool businessman who had retired to Storrs, his 1,000-acre estate along Windermere, organized a gala honoring the former prime minister and conservative icon George Canning. Among the Tory luminaries who attended were the Scottish writers Walter Scott, John Wilson, and John Gibson Lockhart (see Barker, 579). In a 22–31 August letter to Maria Jewsbury, Dora gave a wickedly candid report of the breakfast the Wordsworths hosted for these writers at Rydal Mount (LDW, 23–25).</span></div></div> – I went to Hallsteads <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note224" id="Note224_return"><sup class="super">
            (224)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Home of the Marshalls. DW spent a week there in September (Letters, 4:392).</span></div></div> – returned to consecration with <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Marshall">C. Marshall</a> <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note225" id="Note225_return"><sup class="super">
            (225)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Cordelia, the Marshalls’ 22-year-old daughter, who was close to both DW and Dora. </span></div></div> … – Broken weather since[.] Mary W. went to Harrowgate with Mrs H[utchinson] … Many fine days, but mostly damp oppressive heat – a plague of catterpillars in gardens.</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p>Now (October 7<sup>th</sup>) It will be a month on Monday since M.W. went to H[arrogate]. They are all now on their way southward – <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Luff">Mrs Luff</a> to London, John to Oxf., the rest to Coleorton. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note226" id="Note226_return"><sup class="super">
            (226)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>After hosting visitors throughout the summer, the Wordsworths scattered in the fall. John returned to Oxford, and MW and Mrs. Hutchinson met up with SH and WW at the Beaumonts’ Leicestershire estate, Coleorton. DW wrote on 18 October, “It will be fortnight on Thursday since Dora and Willy and I were left alone—thoroughly alone—for Mrs Luff accompanied [WW, MW, and SH] to Manchester on her way to London, summoned thither by the dangerous illness of Lady Farquhar” (Letters, 4:392). Lady Maria Farquhar and her husband, Sir Robert Townsend Farquhar (1776–1830, DNB) had become friends with Mrs. Luf…</span></div></div> Miss Honeyman <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note227" id="Note227_return"><sup class="super">
            (227)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Mary Honeyman (1775–1851) was the unmarried daughter of a Presbyterian minister from Penrith who may have known DW in connection with her parents having taken in the orphaned Sarah Green in 1808 (Letters, 4:392n3; Cumberland Pacquet, 14 January 1851, 3). Regarding the warm friendship that developed during this visit, DW wrote on 18 October, “Miss Honeyman has been staying with us a fortnight – very happy – She has had a whole summer of quiet rambling, and returns with pleasure to her winter duties at Penrith. She has a small house there – has a comfortable independence of her own making, and i…</span></div></div> has been here a week.</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">[October 6<sup>th</sup>]</span><br/> The party off yesterday at 4 o’clock – – a little rain, but pleasant day, &amp; not so very hot. – <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Cookson">John Cookson</a> &amp; Miss Fothergill <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note228" id="Note228_return"><sup class="super">
            (228)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>John was the 21-year-old son of the Kendal Cooksons. Miss Fothergill is unidentified. </span></div></div> met Miss H[oneyman] &amp; me on road to Ambleside, turned back. Waterfalls – Luncheon &amp;c &amp;c – &amp; off before dinner. – Went down to visit Harrison’s wife <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note229" id="Note229_return"><sup class="super">
            (229)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Perhaps Catherine Harrison, the wife of WW’s old friend Anthony (see note for 17 December), as DW consistently refers to her cousin Dorothy Harrison as “Mrs. Harrison.” </span></div></div> &amp; J Carter <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note230" id="Note230_return"><sup class="super">
            (230)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>John Carter (1797–1863), WW’s clerk from 1813 until the poet’s death in 1850. </span></div></div> &amp; <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Robinson">Robinsons</a> before Tea. Then set to at the <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Harden">Hardens’</a>, by fire side.</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">October 7<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Soft grey morning – hopeful for Langdale but heavy rain set in – &amp; now (at 10 o’clock) is falling pell-mell. – Clears in the afternoon, brisk wind &amp; sunshine. Miss H[oneyman] &amp; I walked to Grasmere – – called at <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Barber">Mr Barbers</a>, M Fishers, <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note231" id="Note231_return"><sup class="super">
            (231)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Likely Mary Dawson Fisher and Mary Dawson Fisher, the Wordsworths’ former maid who had married John Fisher in 1817 after having born him at least one child (GJ, 162, 257; WT MS WLMS 7 / 163).</span></div></div> <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#De">Mrs De Q’s</a> and <a class="link_ref" href="Quincey">Mrs De Q’s</a> &amp;c. Comet at night[.] Jos &amp; Willy quarrel – Jos off <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note232" id="Note232_return"><sup class="super">
            (232)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Possibly either the Hardens’ 20-year-old son or the Joseph mentioned in DW’s entry for 7 December 1824. </span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">8<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Fine morning – at 7 – packed up for Windermere. Rain comes on – &amp; continues (heavy) all day. <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Robinson">Tom Robinson</a> <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note233" id="Note233_return"><sup class="super">
            (233)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Lt. Tom Robinson became such a fixture at Rydal that autumn that word of his designs on Dora soon reached SH at Coleorton. In a gossipy 3 November letter, SH seems to reference neither party having a fortune when she quips, “Tom Robinson finds Rydal so attractive that he is a poor support to his Mother – This is news for Mary, but she need not fear taxation, on the part of the Lady – Dora I mean – &amp; the youth also is too wise. He sees enough of love in a Cottage at the foot of the hill” (WT MS WLMS H / 1 / 6 / 5).</span></div></div> arrives from [ ] – I go with him to tea below – still rains – home [with me?] to supper. Murray drowned <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note234" id="Note234_return"><sup class="super">
            (234)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Obscure but possibly pertains to the publisher John Murray. While he most certainly hadn’t drowned, his name had become a byword at Rydal Mount in 1825 for his supposedly high-handed treatment of WW (Letters, 4:397).</span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 9<sup>th</sup></span><br/> T[om] R[obinson] to breakfast[.] Letter from <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Jewsbury">Miss Jewsbury</a> – The party left <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Marshall">Marshalls’</a> on Tuesday morning. – Heavy rain comes on at Church – continuous &amp; in afternoon I walked to Scandale Bridge <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note235" id="Note235_return"><sup class="super">
            (235)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Bridge over Scandale Beck, midway between Rydal and Ambleside. </span></div></div> with Mrs Carr[,] Miss H[oneyman], T. R &amp; D. [gone?] to waterfall <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note236" id="Note236_return"><sup class="super">
            (236)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Likely Stock Ghyll Force outside Ambleside.</span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 10<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Heavy rain, in afternoon. Mr R[obinson] &amp; Leonard E <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note237" id="Note237_return"><sup class="super">
            (237)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Leonard Edmunds, the 23-year-old son of the Ambleside solicitor and political operative John Edmunds and, given DW’s use of his first name, likely an old friend of the Wordsworth children. In 1833 he would receive a royal appointment as Clerk of the Patents (Carlisle Journal, 2 September 1833, 2).</span></div></div> to dinner. I at Ambleside in morning with Miss H[oneyman] – wrote to Mr T. &amp; Mrs C about house. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note238" id="Note238_return"><sup class="super">
            (238)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>She presumably was informing Tillbrooke and Mrs. Cookson that the Wordsworths may need to vacate Rydal Mount in the months ahead (see note for 24 February entry).</span></div></div> [Rise?] in Weather glass <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note239" id="Note239_return"><sup class="super">
            (239)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>This seemingly suggests that, besides the thermometer referenced elsewhere in RJ, the Wordsworths owned a weather glass (or storm glass). Invented ca. 1780, these fashionable (and generally unreliable) devices consisted of a slender glass tube filled with a chemical mixture that supposedly crystalized as a storm approached (see McConnell and Collins, “Will the True Originator”).</span></div></div> – wrote Mrs Marshall</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 11<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Very fine afternoon. Mr F. Fleming <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note240" id="Note240_return"><sup class="super">
            (240)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Rev. Fletcher Fleming of Rydal Chapel.</span></div></div> &amp; Miss Dawson call. Walk with Miss H[oneyman] to Grasmere – Carters <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note241" id="Note241_return"><sup class="super">
            (241)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>See note for 7 October.</span></div></div> &amp; Mr Fox <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note242" id="Note242_return"><sup class="super">
            (242)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Unidentified.</span></div></div> at Mr Barbers – cross water.</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 12<sup>th</sup></span> <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note243" id="Note243_return"><sup class="super">
            (243)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>This and the ensuing three entries describe DW’s second multiday journey to Coniston in the past few months, albeit in much less detail than her earlier entries from early July. </span></div></div> <br/> In cart to Coniston <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note244" id="Note244_return"><sup class="super">
            (244)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>See note for 5 July.</span></div></div> with Miss H[oneyman] – clear cool air – hazy mountains yet sunshine below. – Heavy shower at night.</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 12<sup>th</sup></span> <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note245" id="Note245_return"><sup class="super">
            (245)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>DW mistakenly dates consecutive entries the 12th. Her dating would get back on track on Saturday, 15 October. </span></div></div> <br/> Lovely morning – out on Lake. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note246" id="Note246_return"><sup class="super">
            (246)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Coniston Water.</span></div></div> – D. &amp; T[om] R[obinson] arrive to dinner. We depart after. Infernal Regions of Backbarrow – Raging River – altogether awful. Immense illuminated Holes [–] <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note247" id="Note247_return"><sup class="super">
            (247)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>White-water torrents and weir-holes in the River Leven at Backbarrow, a village in south-central Cumbria, were frequently cited instances of the sublime (or, as DW puts it here, the “awful”). In Antiquities of Furness, Thomas West describes how the Leven “falls with great rapidity for the space of two miles, dashing its waters against the rugged rocks, which oppose its course, through Backbarrow, forming several cascades” (36).</span></div></div> Supper &amp; bed at Newby Bridge <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note248" id="Note248_return"><sup class="super">
            (248)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>In the approximately four hours between dinner and the 7:00 p.m. mid-October sunset, the party covered nearly 15 miles: 13 from Coniston and Backbarrow and another mile and a half to Newby Bridge. It seems likely, then, that the first leg of their itinerary, wherein they traversed the length of Coniston Water, was made by boat. </span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 13<sup>th</sup></span> – Very fine morning. – Rain comes on – Stormy Fury – foolish Sail-Boat. Hat lost – – Rainy journey – no views at Station – very fine after Bowness. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note249" id="Note249_return"><sup class="super">
            (249)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>From Newby Bridge, they seem to have rather ill-advisedly (as DW would have it) hired a boat to take them roughly eight miles up Windermere’s western shore to the viewing station at Claife Heights, which West had popularized in his 1778 Guide to the Lakes. From there, they took the ferry to Bowness, on Windermere’s eastern shore.</span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 15<sup>th</sup></span> Bright morning – showers … – &amp; showery afternoon – prepare to go to <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Low">Low Wood</a> and <a class="link_ref" href="Wood">Low Wood</a> – meet the Mackintoshes <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note250" id="Note250_return"><sup class="super">
            (250)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>An exhausted DW reported on 18 October that the Scottish barrister and politician Sir James Mackintosh (1765–1832) and his daughter had been the “last of [their] Lakers” to visit during “the most bustling summer ever remembered.” Having known him since at least 1812, she wrote, “Sir James looks wonderfully well, considering the wearing life he has led—politics—law—India—house of Commons wrangling!” (Letters, 4:392–93; see also 3:45, 4:388).</span></div></div> at Waterfall <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note251" id="Note251_return"><sup class="super">
            (251)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Stock Ghyll Force near Ambleside.</span></div></div> –</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 16<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Showery – but pleasant. Mackintoshes to Luncheon [–] T. Robinson [–] Mr Barber to Tea.</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 17<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Cold &amp; showery – to Mrs Luffs – wrote to Coleorton <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note252" id="Note252_return"><sup class="super">
            (252)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Home of the Beaumonts, where WW and MW were currently staying. </span></div></div> – &amp; Mrs L. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note253" id="Note253_return"><sup class="super">
            (253)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Mary Laing, who, after visiting Rydal in 1822 with her brother, the antiquarian David Laing, had corresponded regularly with DW (Letters, 4:154n, 233, 238, 394).</span></div></div> The Robinsons to Tea and Cards</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 18<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Very rainy [–] wrote to Mrs Clarkson <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note254" id="Note254_return"><sup class="super">
            (254)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Her old friend and regular correspondent Catherine Clarkson (see Letters, 4:391–94).</span></div></div> ... Miss H[oneyman] left us in the Evening. Stormy walk – and all to Tea at Mr Robinsons [–] very heavy rain at night</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 19</span><br/> Dora was to have gone to Coniston – no horse for Mr R – all walked to Ambleside. <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Myers">Julia</a> to dinner – very bright &amp; cold but tremendous rain at night[.] Julia stays. <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Ann">Anne</a> and <a class="link_ref" href="Dawson">Anne</a> poorly unknown to us <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note255" id="Note255_return"><sup class="super">
            (255)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Their housemaid Anne Harrison.</span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 20<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Very cold – very clear – mountains snowy. Fern bright – smooth-topped white hills – very like alps – green <span style="text-decoration:underline">treey</span> ridge below. Dora &amp; T[om] R[obinson] to Coniston. Before dinner I called on Mr de Q <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note256" id="Note256_return"><sup class="super">
            (256)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The first appearance in RJ of Thomas De Quincey, who, after an 18-month absence, had rejoined his family at his father-in-law’s farm near Rydal.</span></div></div> ... <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Barlow">Mrs Barlow</a> &amp; Miss Walker <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note257" id="Note257_return"><sup class="super">
            (257)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Perhaps a relative or friend staying with the Barlows at The Wood, as in July 1826 Dora alluded to “two Mr Walkers” being with them in Troutbeck (LDW, 33–34). Another possibility is Hannah Walker, whom DW had met in Eusemere a few weeks earlier and afterward described as “a perfect specimen of beauty in old age” (Letters, 4:392).</span></div></div> on returning dined with us, &amp; Miss Honeyman – Miss Nelson <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note258" id="Note258_return"><sup class="super">
            (258)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Unidentified.</span></div></div> to tea – I went to Ambleside – [poor?] Mr Ladyman <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note259" id="Note259_return"><sup class="super">
            (259)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Presumably Joseph Ladyman, proprietor of the Salutation Inn below Stock Gill in Ambleside. He had possibly fallen upon financial hardship, as the inn would be put up for lease in 1828 (Lancaster Gazette, 6 December 1828, p. 2).</span></div></div> – .... Clear moonlight night [–] read Life of Charles <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note260" id="Note260_return"><sup class="super">
            (260)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Likely Dr. John Lingard’s new biography of Charles I, which appeared as the tenth volume of his monumental History of England from the First Invasion by the Romans (London: Mawman, 1825).</span></div></div> – Willy busy for his journey <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note261" id="Note261_return"><sup class="super">
            (261)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Apparently to join Dora and Tom Robinson at Coniston (as the next entry suggests). </span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 21<sup>st</sup></span><br/> Willy off to Coniston before breakfast – Cold and clear. <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Southey">The Southeys</a> arrive in chaise. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note262" id="Note262_return"><sup class="super">
            (262)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The teenage Southey girls, Bertha and Kate, would stay at Rydal until 11 November. </span></div></div> Stormy and rain comes on[.] Mary came home <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note263" id="Note263_return"><sup class="super">
            (263)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Unclear to which Mary she refers, as MW would not return from Coleorton for another four weeks (see 17 November entry). </span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 22<sup>nd</sup></span><br/> A lovely bright day – warm – in sun – clear air[.] Walk with Southeys to Ambleside – Mr Carr visits Anne. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note264" id="Note264_return"><sup class="super">
            (264)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Visiting their ailing servant Anne (see 19 October) in his capacity as a physician. </span></div></div> Miss Honeyman to dinner &amp; Tea. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note265" id="Note265_return"><sup class="super">
            (265)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>After leaving Rydal Mount on 18 October, Miss Honeyman apparently stayed with others in the vicinity before her return to Penrith. </span></div></div></p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 23<sup>rd</sup></span> mild Rain. Mr Barber comes at dinner time. Walk with him after Church. Splendid sky – purple &amp; ruby hues, in sky &amp; lake – Emerald Isle <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note266" id="Note266_return"><sup class="super">
            (266)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The context suggests she is referring not to Ireland but to the greenness of one of the four small islands in Rydal Water. </span></div></div> [–] Gipsies on hill – <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note267" id="Note267_return"><sup class="super">
            (267)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Gypsy sightings were increasingly rare in rural England during this period, in part because of restrictive measures like the Vagrancy Act of 1824 (Cressy, Gypsies, 148–51). WW’s 1807 poem “Gypsies” was less than sympathetic toward these “wild outcasts of society,” but DW reported to William Pearson in 1830 that “every member of this family” had been captivated by accounts he had gathered from his “vagrant neighbours” (Letters, 5:220).</span></div></div></p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday <span style="text-decoration: line-through">22<sup>nd</sup></span> 23</span><br/> Fine Day – walked to Ambleside – –</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday <span style="text-decoration: line-through">23<sup>rd</sup></span> 24</span><br/> Very fine – Miss Honeyman to dinner</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday <span style="text-decoration: line-through">24<sup>th</sup></span> 25</span><br/> [Cheary?] day for <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Kendal">Kendal</a>. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note268" id="Note268_return"><sup class="super">
            (268)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>A three-day visit to see the Cooksons (see 29 October entry for her return). </span></div></div> Rain at night.</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday <span style="text-decoration: line-through">27</span> 26</span><br/> cold &amp; damp – rainy afternoon</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 28<sup>th</sup></span><br/> a lovely bright day – warm like spring.</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 29</span><br/> Fine afternoon [–] stormy ride, in Gig but pleasant with John Cookson. Left Elizabeth, <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note269" id="Note269_return"><sup class="super">
            (269)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The Cooksons’ chronically ill eldest daughter.</span></div></div> as I found her, – poorly.</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 30<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Very rainy, fierce wind. Went with D to see <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Elliott">the Elliotts</a>. <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Hartley">Hartley</a> to Tea &amp;c</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 31<sup>st</sup></span><br/> Very fine morning – with <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Southey">Bertha</a> to Low Wood &amp;c – – Robinsons to Tea &amp; cards</p></section><section class="section" id="index.xml-body.1_div.13"><header><h1><span style="font-size: 75%">[November 1825]</span></h1></header><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday, Nov<sup>r</sup> 1<sup>st</sup></span><br/> Lovely mild morning. Rain comes on – <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Hartley">Hartley</a> to Dinner – Cards – <a class="link_ref" href="editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Robinson">T[om] R[obinson]</a> – They stayed till ½ past 10</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 2<sup>nd</sup></span><br/> Blustering morning – walk on Terrace – sunny gleam – Fine colouring seen from Field. Cherry-trees &amp;c – – T R. here [–] very bad cold[.] Cards again.</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 3<sup>rd</sup></span><br/> Very rainy &amp; stormy – never out but at <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Robinson">Mr Robinsons</a> in the Evening, &amp; in the morning with <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Southey">B[ertha] &amp; K[ate]</a> at Waterfalls.</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 4<sup>th</sup></span><br/> One of the loveliest of days[.] Walked with B[ertha] &amp; K[ate] to <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Low">Low Wood</a> and <a class="link_ref" href="Wood">Low Wood</a>. Came home in Chaise with Mr R[obinson] returning from Miss H K. <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note270" id="Note270_return"><sup class="super">
            (270)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Henrietta Kearsley, presumably a relative of Charlotte Kearsley Robinson. In Dora’s estimation, this visitor to the area was “very pretty but very insipid” (LDW, 27).</span></div></div> – The [Autumn?] – till Tuesday or Wednesday – [ ] &amp; [ ] – now [beautified?] [beyond?] [ ]. T. R. ill – Cards by ourselves – at night D &amp; I called on <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#De">Mr de Q</a> and <a class="link_ref" href="Quincey">Mr de Q</a>.</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 5<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Dull &amp; wet – alas the Bonfire! <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note271" id="Note271_return"><sup class="super">
            (271)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The annual Guy Fawkes’ Day bonfire, thwarted by rain. </span></div></div> No walk / But Dora had.</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 6<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Blustery showers – <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Barber">Mr Barber</a> came to Dinner. I walked with him by <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Fox">Fox Ghyll</a> and <a class="link_ref" href="Ghyll">Fox Ghyll</a> to <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Ambleside">Ambleside</a> – called at <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Dowling">Miss Dowling’s</a></p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 7<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Bright morning – closes in – Snow – Rain [–] sleet – Anne arrives <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note272" id="Note272_return"><sup class="super">
            (272)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Most likely their housemaid Anne Harrison, returning to service after a period of convalescence (see 19 October entry). </span></div></div> – walk only on Terrace – Sunny Bursts through the Day.</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 8<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Very cold – snow – sleet – walk in heavy rain</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday</span> blustery – ground covered with snow.</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 10<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Hard frost – fierce wind. <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Southey">Southeys</a> did not get off – [Fetched?] <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Myers">Julia</a> from Ambleside – Miss Pritchards – gay cloaks[,] immense Bonnets <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note273" id="Note273_return"><sup class="super">
            (273)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Apparently details from a soiree hosted by their 69-year-old neighbor, Laetia Pritchard, at her Loughrigg home, Croft Lodge. Sara Coleridge and Sara Coleridge mentioned a similar gathering in a November 1820 letter ( WT MS WLMS A / Coleridge, Sara / 3), and in June of that year, SH joked with her then-single cousin, Tom Monkhouse, “You may grow more beautiful every day, after you are married, and old Miss Pritchard, even, will not espy out the half of your charms” (LSH, 182–83). Miss Pritchard would pass away in January 1827 at age 71 (Miscellanea Genealogica et Heraldica 3 [1880], p. 154).</span></div></div></p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 11<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Southeys off – fine frosty day – snow [mountains?], very grand – walked with Dora &amp; Mr T. Robinson by Fox Ghyll to Ambleside. Willy poorly – when we came home.</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 12<sup>th</sup></span><br/> The loveliest of bright days [–] to Ambleside for Willy – ill on Sofa – – sun shining[,] blinds down – –. Mr Barber [come?] ask me to walk after dinner – could not. Dora stayed so long on her ride –</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 13<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Very cold – very dull &amp; rainy afternoon – walked in rain to Grasmere.</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 14<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Robinsons to tea [–] a beautiful day – sunny &amp; bright – garden clearing [–] to Mrs de Quinceys</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 15</span><br/> The same lovely weather – I walked with D. We made calls – Willy rode with Mr Barber – cards at 8 o’ night – Mr &amp; Mrs R –</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 16<sup>th</sup> Nov<sup>r</sup></span><br/> Sara H[utchinson] arrived – showery day</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 17<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Very stormy[.] Wm &amp; M. arrived <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note274" id="Note274_return"><sup class="super">
            (274)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>SH and WW had been away for six weeks, primarily at Coleorton, and MW for over two months (Letters, 4:404).</span></div></div></p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 18<sup>th</sup></span> – Rainy – walked only on Terrace.</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 19</span><br/> Fine clean air – a shower or two – Rode in cart with new pony with Willy –</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 20</span> Very wet – [ ] at Mr Robinsons – walked an hour in rain on Terrace with D – &amp; alone</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday</span> – Stormy wind – showers. Dr [ ] in Evening – Walk with W &amp; T[om] R[obinson] – Mr de Q. –</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday <span style="text-decoration: line-through">21<sup>st</sup></span> 22</span><br/> Showery – Fine walk on Terrace by moonlight with W &amp; T R</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday <span style="text-decoration: line-through">22</span> <sup>nd</sup> 23</span><br/> T R departs – showers</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday <span style="text-decoration: line-through">23 <sup>rd</sup></span> 24</span><br/> Walked with Wm. round by Skelwith Bridge <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note275" id="Note275_return"><sup class="super">
            (275)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Hamlet three and a half miles south of Rydal on the other side of Loughrigg. </span></div></div> – various Calls</p></div><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 25<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Rain again – at night very heavy –</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 26<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Still rainy &amp; blustery</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 27<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Snow showers. Hail – Sunshine. Wm. &amp; M and Willy at Grasmere Church – walk with <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Carr">Mrs Carr</a></p><div class="wrapper"><p>All this week neglected <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note276" id="Note276_return"><sup class="super">
            (276)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>That is, neglected her diary, suggesting she was resuming on 3 December. </span></div></div> – Cold and stormy – – Walk every day –</p></div></section><section class="section" id="index.xml-body.1_div.14"><header><h1><span style="font-size: 75%">[December 1825]</span></h1></header><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Saturday 3<sup>rd</sup></span> William [Parker?] Funeral – snow on ground – foggy –</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Sunday 4<sup>th</sup></span> – Cold – snow on ground – –</p><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Monday 5<sup>th</sup></span> – Very bright – Sloppy roads – snow on ground – walked to <span class="ref">Brathay</span> with Wm. W[illy] followed</p><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Tuesday 6<sup>th</sup></span><br/> Snow almost gone. Walked to Elter Water <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note277" id="Note277_return"><sup class="super">
            (277)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Village and small lake three miles southwest of Rydal, on the other side of Loughrigg. </span></div></div> – Wm &amp; <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#De">Mr de Q</a> and <a class="link_ref" href="Quincey">Mr de Q</a> – Mr Huddleston <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note278" id="Note278_return"><sup class="super">
            (278)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Possibly Rev. Andrew Hudleston (1777–1851), perpetual curate of St. Nicholas in Whitehaven (Letters, 4:697).</span></div></div> – misty but pleasant</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Wednesday 7<sup>th</sup></span><br/> To Wood <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note279" id="Note279_return"><sup class="super">
            (279)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The Wood, home of the Barlows.</span></div></div> in Cart with D – back with Willy – very pleasant – Rain in evening.</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Thursday 9 (8)<sup>th</sup></span> <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note280" id="Note280_return"><sup class="super">
            (280)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>DW’s marking.</span></div></div> – Lovely day – &amp; rosy sunset – – I not well. The Rest with <a class="link_ref" href="/editions/DW/editions.2022.DW.RJ-1-reading.html#Barber">Mr Barber</a> planning new house <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note281" id="Note281_return"><sup class="super">
            (281)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>In the eventuality they would need to move from Rydal Mount.</span></div></div> – He dines –</p></div><div class="wrapper"><p><span style="font-weight:bold">Friday 10 (9)<sup>th</sup></span> <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note282" id="Note282_return"><sup class="super">
            (282)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>The final entry in this notebook and for 1825. She resumed her diary on 10 February 1826 in a new notebook (DCMS 104.2). </span></div></div> – Dull rainy morning – [Brewing?]. –</p></div></section><section class="section" id="index.xml-body.1_div.15"><header><h1><span style="font-size: 75%">[Two blank pages]</span></h1></header></section><section class="section" id="index.xml-body.1_div.16"><header><h1><span style="font-size: 75%">[Last notebook page]</span></h1></header><div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note283" id="Note283_return"><sup class="super">
            (283)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>This list of favorite Bible verses appears upside down, in pencil, and in DW’s hand on the final notebook page (see fig. 3). Perhaps suggesting the focus of her personal scripture study during 1825, the New Testament citations come exclusively from the epistles of Paul and the Old Testament ones from the Book of Job and the Psalms. </span></div></div><div class="wrapper"><p>2<sup>nd</sup> Chap Philippians 6 verse <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note284" id="Note284_return"><sup class="super">
