            (302)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>Edward Quillinan (1791–1851, DNB), the former army officer and future husband of Dora who had retired to Rydal in 1821 to live near his poetic idol, WW. In the wake of his wife’s tragic 1822 death, Quillinan and his two daughters had settled in London and Kent; but, by SH’s report, he returned to Rydal in late August 1825 for the consecration of the new chapel (WT MS WLL / Hutchinson, Sara / 2 / 110a).</span></div></div> Miss Honeyman <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note303" id="Note303_return"><sup class="super">
            (303)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>See note for 7 October entry.</span></div></div> <br/> <span class="ref">Mrs Barlow – Miss Barlow</span><br/> Q[uestion]? – Plague in Florence 1543 <div class="textHoverbox"><a class="note_back" href="#Note304" id="Note304_return"><sup class="super">
            (304)
          </sup></a><div class="tooltip"><span>This cryptic note appears upside down at the bottom of the back inside cover. DW’s query possibly grew out of her rereading of the Florentine poet Dante (see 13 December entry and note) and presumably concerned the Black Plague that ravaged mid-fourteenth century Florence (30 years after Dante’s death). </span></div></div></p></div></section></div>